# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: floating-battery
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Union navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Union navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] To fight an offensive war, the Confederacy purchased arms in Britain and converted British-built ships into commerce raiders, which targeted United States Merchant Marine ships in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy smuggled 600,000 arms, enabling it to continue fighting for two more years.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] As insurance rates soared, American-flagged ships largely ceased traveling in international waters, though some were reflagged with European flags, which allowed them to continue operating.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] After the conclusion of the Civil War, the US government demanded Britain reimburse it for the damage caused by blockade runners and raiders outfitted in British ports.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Britain paid the US$15 million in 1871, which covered costs associated with commerce raiding but nothing more.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Although the Confederacy hoped Britain and France would join them against the Union, this was never likely, so they sought to bring them in as mediators.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Union worked to block this and threatened war against any country that recognized the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In 1861, Southerners voluntarily embargoed cotton shipments, hoping to start an economic depression in Europe that would force Britain to enter the war, but this failed.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Worse, Europe turned to Egypt and India for cotton, which they found superior, hindering the South's postwar recovery.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Cotton diplomacy proved a failure, because Europe had a surplus of cotton, while the 1860–62 crop failures in Europe made the North's grain exports critically important.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] It also helped turn European opinion against the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] It was said that "King Corn was more powerful than King Cotton", as US grain increased from a quarter to almost half of British imports.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Meanwhile, the war created jobs for arms makers, ironworkers, and ships to transport weapons.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's administration initially struggled to appeal to European public opinion.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] At first, diplomats explained that the US was not committed to ending slavery and emphasized legal arguments about the unconstitutionality of secession.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate representatives, however, focused on their struggle for liberty, commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] European government leaders welcomed the fragmentation of the ascendant American Republic." However, a European public with liberal sensibilities remained, which the US sought to appeal to by building connections with the international press.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] By 1861, Union diplomats like Carl Schurz realized emphasizing the war against slavery was the Union's most effective moral asset in swaying European public opinion.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Seward was concerned an overly radical case for reunification would distress European merchants with cotton interests; even so, he supported a widespread campaign of public diplomacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] US minister to Britain Charles Francis Adams proved adept and convinced Britain not to challenge the Union blockade.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy purchased warships from commercial shipbuilders in Britain, with the most famous being the CSS *Alabama*, which caused considerable damage and led to serious postwar disputes.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] However, public opinion against slavery in Britain created a political liability for politicians, where the anti-slavery movement was powerful.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] War loomed in late 1861 between the US and Britain over the *Trent* Affair, which began when US Navy personnel boarded the British ship *Trent* and seized two Confederate diplomats.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] However, London and Washington smoothed this over after Lincoln released the two men.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Prince Albert left his deathbed to issue diplomatic instructions to Lord Lyons during the *Trent* Affair.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] His request was honored, and, as a result, the British response to the US was toned down, helping avert war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In 1862, the British government considered mediating between the Union and Confederacy, though such an offer would have risked war with the US.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] British prime minister Lord Palmerston reportedly read *Uncle Tom's Cabin* three times when deciding what his decision would be.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Union victory at the Battle of Antietam caused the British to delay this decision.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] The Emancipation Proclamation increased the political liability of supporting the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Realizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed the Habsburg Austrian archduke Maximilian I as emperor.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Despite sympathy for the Confederacy, France's seizure of Mexico deterred it from war with the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate offers late in the war to end slavery in return for diplomatic recognition were not seriously considered by London or Paris.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] After 1863, the Polish revolt against Russia further distracted the European powers and ensured they remained neutral.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] Russia supported the Union, largely because it believed the US counterbalanced its geopolitical rival, the UK.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p01] In 1863, the Imperial Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Eastern theater refers to the military operations east of the Appalachian Mountains, including Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, the District of Columbia, and the coastal fortifications and seaports of North Carolina.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan took command of the Union Army of the Potomac on July 26, 1861, and the war began in earnest in 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Ohio forces would advance through Kentucky into Tennessee.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Missouri Department would drive south along the Mississippi River.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The westernmost attack would originate from Kansas.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Confederate force in the Eastern theater was the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Army originated as the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac, which was organized on June 20, 1861, from all operational forces in Northern Virginia.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] On July 20 and 21, the Army of the Shenandoah and forces from the District of Harpers Ferry were added.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Units from the Army of the Northwest were merged into the Army of the Potomac between March 14 and May 17, 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Potomac was renamed *Army of Northern Virginia* on March 14.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Peninsula was merged into it on April 12, 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] When Virginia declared its secession in April 1861, Robert E.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lee chose to follow his home state, despite his desire for the country to remain intact and an offer of a senior Union command.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In his four-volume biography of Lee published in 1934 and 1935, historian Douglas S.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Freeman wrote that the army received its final name from Lee when he issued orders assuming command on June 1, 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] However, Freeman wrote, Lee corresponded with Brigadier General Joseph E.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston, his predecessor in army command, before that date and referred to Johnston's command as the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Part of the confusion results from the fact that Johnston commanded the Department of Northern Virginia as of October 22, 1861, and the name Army of Northern Virginia was seen as an informal consequence of its parent department's name.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Jefferson Davis and Johnston did not adopt the name, but the organization of units as of March 14 was clearly the same organization that Lee received on June 1, and is generally referred to as the Army of Northern Virginia, even if that is correct only in retrospect.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] On July 4 at Harper's Ferry, Colonel Thomas J.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson assigned Jeb Stuart command of all cavalry companies of the Army of the Shenandoah, and Jackson eventually commanded the Army of Northern Virginia's cavalry.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Called the "Philippi Races" because of its brevity, Philippi, Virginia (now Philippi, WV) was the scene of the first organized land action of the American Civil War, on June 3, 1861.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In July 1861, in the first in a series of prominent battles in the war, Union Army troops commanded by Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Irvin McDowell attacked Confederate forces, which were under the command of Beauregard near the national capital in Washington.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy repelled the attack in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of the battle, the Union appeared to hold the upper hand.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union Army routed Confederate forces, then holding defensive positions, but Confederate reinforcements under Joseph E.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston arrived from the Shenandoah Valley by railroad, and the battle's course quickly changed.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] A brigade of Virginians, commanded by Thomas J.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson, then a relatively unknown brigadier general from Virginia Military Institute, stood its ground, leading to Jackson earning the nickname "Stonewall".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln urged the Union Army to commence offensive operations against Confederate forces, which led General George B.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan, in the spring of 1862, to attack Virginia by way of the peninsula between the York River and James River southeast of Richmond.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan's army reached the gates of Richmond in the Peninsula campaign.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Also in the spring of 1862, in Shenandoah Valley, Jackson led his Valley Campaign, during which he employed rapid and unpredictable movements on interior lines.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson's 17,000 troops marched 646 miles (1,040 km) in 48 days, during which they won minor battles as they engaged three Union armies, comprising 52,000 men, including those of Nathaniel P.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont, preventing them from reinforcing the Union offensive against Richmond.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The swiftness of Jackson's troops earned them the nickname foot cavalry.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston halted McClellan's advance at the Battle of Seven Pines, but he was wounded in the battle, and Robert E.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lee and his senior subordinates, James Longstreet and Stonewall Jackson, defeated McClellan in the Seven Days Battles, forcing McClellan's retreat.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] During the Northern Virginia Campaign, which included the Second Battle of Bull Run, Confederate forces registered another important military victory.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan resisted General-in-Chief Halleck's orders to send reinforcements to John Pope's Union Army of Virginia, which enabled Lee's Confederate forces to defeat twice the number of combined enemy troops.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Emboldened by Second Bull Run, Confederate forces launched their first invasion of the North in the Maryland Campaign during which Lee led 45,000 Army of Northern Virginia troops across the Potomac River into Maryland on September 5.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln then restored Pope's troops to McClellan, and McClellan and Lee clashed in the Battle of Antietam near Sharpsburg, Maryland, on September 17, 1862, which proved the bloodiest single day in both the Civil War and US military history.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan failed to respond in any measurable way to Lee's attempt to invade the North at Antietam, leading to his replacement by Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Burnside led Union Army troops in the Battle of Fredericksburg, where they were defeated on December 13, 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Over 12,000 Union soldiers were killed or wounded during futile attempts by Union troops to launch frontal assaults against Marye's Heights.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] After the battle, Burnside was replaced by Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Hooker, too, proved unable to defeat Lee's army; despite having more than twice as many troops as Lee, Hooker's Chancellorsville Campaign proved ineffective, and he was soundly defeated in the Battle of Chancellorsville, which was fought between April 30 and May 6, 1863.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Chancellorsville is known as Lee's "perfect battle" because his risky decision to divide his army paid off.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] During the Battle of Chancellorsville, Stonewall Jackson was shot in his left arm and right hand by friendly fire, leading to the amputation of his arm, and he died of pneumonia.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The fiercest fighting of the battle—and the second bloodiest day of the Civil War—occurred on May 3 as Lee launched multiple attacks against the Union position at Chancellorsville.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] That same day, John Sedgwick advanced across the Rappahannock River, defeated the small Confederate force at Marye's Heights in the Second Battle of Fredericksburg, and then moved westward, but Confederate forces succeeded in delaying Union forces in the Battle of Salem Church.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] George Meade during Lee's second invasion of the North, in June.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In the Battle of Gettysburg, which proved the war's bloodiest and one of its most strategically significant, Meade defeated Lee in a three-day battle between July 1 and 3, 1863.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Gettysburg caused over 50,000 Union and Confederate casualties, but also proved the war's turning point, altering the course of the war in the Union's favor.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Pickett's Charge, launched July 3, on the final day of the Battle of Gettysburg, is considered the high-water mark of the Confederacy, representing the collapse of any credible prospect that the Confederacy could prevail in the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] At Gettysburg, Lee's Army of Northern Virginia suffered 28,000 casualties versus Meade's 23,000, and Lee was repelled in a failed attempt to invade and occupy Union territory.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Western theater refers to military operations between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, including Alabama, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi, North Carolina, Kentucky, South Carolina, Tennessee, and parts of Louisiana.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Union forces in this theater were the Army of the Tennessee and Army of the Cumberland, named for the two rivers, Tennessee River and Cumberland River.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] After Meade's inconclusive fall campaign, Lincoln turned to the Western theater for new leadership.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] At the same time, the Confederate stronghold of Vicksburg surrendered, giving the Union control of the Mississippi River, permanently isolating the western Confederacy, and producing the new leader Lincoln needed, Ulysses S.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of Tennessee, which served as the primary Confederate force in the Western theater, was formed on November 20, 1862, when General Braxton Bragg renamed the former Army of Mississippi.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] While Confederate forces had successes in the Eastern theater, they were defeated many times in the West.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's key strategist and tactician in the West was Ulysses S.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant, who led the Union to victories in battles at Fort Henry (February 6, 1862) and Fort Donelson (February 11 to 16, 1862), earning him the nickname of "Unconditional Surrender" Grant.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] With these victories, the Union gained control of the Tennessee and Cumberland Rivers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Nathan Bedford Forrest rallied nearly 4,000 Confederate troops and led them to escape across the Cumberland River.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Nashville and central Tennessee fell to the Union, leading to attrition of local food supplies and livestock and a breakdown in social organization.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate general Leonidas Polk subsequently invaded Columbus, Kentucky, which ended Kentucky's policy of neutrality and turned it against the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant used river transport and Andrew Hull Foote's gunboats of the Western Flotilla, threatening the Confederacy's "Gibraltar of the West" in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Although rebuffed at Belmont, Grant cut off Columbus.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces, lacking their gunboats, were forced to retreat and the Union took control of west Kentucky and opened Tennessee in March 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Shiloh, in Shiloh, Tennessee, in April 1862, Confederate forces launched a surprise attack on Union forces, pushing them back to the Tennessee River as night fell.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Over that night, however, the Navy landed reinforcements, and Grant counterattacked.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant and the Union ultimately won a decisive victory in the first battle with a high number of casualties in what proved to be the first in a series of such battles.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces lost Albert Sidney Johnston, considered their finest general, before Lee emerged to assume command.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] One of the early Union objectives was to capture the Mississippi River, which would permit it to cut the Confederacy in half.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Mississippi was opened to Union traffic to the southern border of Tennessee after it took Island No.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] 10, New Madrid, Missouri, and then Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, the Union Navy captured New Orleans.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] "The key to the river was New Orleans, the South's largest port [and] greatest industrial center." US naval forces under Farragut ran past Confederate defenses south of New Orleans.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces abandoned the city, giving the Union a critical anchor in the deep South, which allowed Union forces to move up the Mississippi.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Memphis fell to Union forces on June 6, 1862, allowing it to serve as a key base for further Union advances south along the Mississippi.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] On the Mississippi River, the Union took every fortress city with the exception of Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] But Confederate control of Vicksburg was sufficient in preventing the Union from controlling the entire river.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Bragg's second invasion of Kentucky in the Confederate Heartland Offensive included initial successes, including Kirby Smith's triumph in the Battle of Richmond and the capture of the Kentucky capital of Frankfort, Kentucky, on September 3, 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The campaign ended with a meaningless victory over Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Don Carlos Buell at the Battle of Perryville, and Bragg was forced to end his attempt to invade and control Kentucky.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lacking logistical support and infantry recruits, Bragg was instead forced to retreat, and ended up being narrowly defeated by Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] William Rosecrans in the Battle of Stones River in Tennessee in what proved to be the culmination of the Stones River Campaign.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] US naval forces assisted Grant in the long, complex Vicksburg Campaign, which resulted in Confederate forces surrendering in the Battle of Vicksburg in July 1863, which cemented Union control of the Mississippi River in one of the war's turning points.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The one clear Confederate victory in the West was the Battle of Chickamauga.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] After Rosecrans' successful Tullahoma Campaign, Bragg, reinforced by Lt.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] James Longstreet's Corps, defeated Rosecrans, despite the defensive stand of Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Rosecrans retreated to Chattanooga, Tennessee, where Bragg was then besieged in the Chattanooga campaign.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant marched to the relief of Rosecrans, where he led the defeat of Bragg in the Third Battle of Chattanooga, eventually causing Longstreet to abandon his Knoxville Campaign and driving Confederate forces out of Tennessee and opening a route to Atlanta and the heart of the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Trans-Mississippi theater refers to military operations west of the Mississippi, encompassing most of Missouri, Arkansas, most of Louisiana, and the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's command was the Trans-Mississippi Division, or the Military Division of West Mississippi.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The first major battle of the Trans-Mississippi theater was the Battle of Wilson's Creek (August 1861).
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates were driven from Missouri early in the war as a result of the Battle of Pea Ridge.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Extensive guerrilla warfare characterized the trans-Mississippi region, as the Confederacy lacked the troops and logistics to support regular armies that could challenge Union control.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Roving Confederate bands such as Quantrill's Raiders terrorized the countryside, striking military installations and civilian settlements.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The "Sons of Liberty" and "Order of the American Knights" attacked pro-Union people, elected officeholders, and unarmed uniformed soldiers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] These partisans could not be driven out of Missouri, until an entire regular Union infantry division was engaged.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] By 1864, these violent activities harmed the nationwide antiwar movement organizing against the re-election of Lincoln.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri not only stayed in the Union, but Lincoln took 70 percent of the vote to win re-election.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Small-scale military actions south and west of Missouri sought to control Indian Territory and New Mexico Territory for the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Glorieta Pass was the decisive battle of the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union repulsed Confederate incursions into New Mexico in 1862, and the exiled Arizona government withdrew into Texas.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In the Indian Territory, civil war broke out within tribes.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] About 12,000 Indian warriors fought for the Confederacy but fewer for the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The most prominent Cherokee was Brigadier General Stand Watie, the last Confederate general to surrender.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] After the fall of Vicksburg in July 1863, Jefferson Davis informed General Kirby Smith in Texas that he could expect no further help from east of the Mississippi.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Although he lacked resources to beat Union armies, he built up a formidable arsenal at Tyler, along with his own Kirby Smithdom economy, a virtual "independent fiefdom" in Texas, including railroad construction and international smuggling.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union, in turn, did not directly engage him.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's 1864 Red River Campaign to take Shreveport, Louisiana, failed and Texas remained in Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The lower seaboard theater refers to military and naval operations that occurred near the coastal areas of the Southeast as well as the southern part of the Mississippi.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Union naval activities were dictated by the Anaconda Plan.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] One of the earliest battles was fought in November 1861 at Port Royal Sound, south of Charleston.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Much of the war along the South Carolina coast concentrated on capturing Charleston.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In attempting to capture Charleston, the Union military tried two approaches: by land over James or Morris Islands or through the harbor.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Confederates were able to drive back each attack.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] A famous land attack was the Second Battle of Fort Wagner, in which the 54th Massachusetts Infantry took part.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union suffered a serious defeat, losing 1,515 soldiers while the Confederates lost only 174.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] However, the 54th was hailed for its valor, which encouraged the general acceptance of the recruitment of African American soldiers into the Union Army, which reinforced the Union's numerical advantage.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Fort Pulaski on the Georgia coast was an early target for the Union navy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Following the capture of Port Royal, an expedition was organized with engineer troops under the command of Captain Quincy Adams Gillmore, forcing a Confederate surrender.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army occupied the fort for the rest of the war after repairing it.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, a Union naval task force commanded by Commander David Dixon Porter attacked Forts Jackson and St.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Philip, which guarded the river approach to New Orleans from the south.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] While part of the fleet bombarded the forts, other vessels forced a break in the obstructions in the river and enabled the rest of the fleet to steam upriver to the city.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Benjamin Butler landed near the forts and forced their surrender.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Butler's controversial command of New Orleans earned him the nickname "Beast".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The following year, the Union Army of the Gulf commanded by Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Banks laid siege to Port Hudson for nearly eight weeks, the longest siege in US military history.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates attempted to defend with the Bayou Teche Campaign but surrendered after Vicksburg.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] These surrenders gave the Union control over the Mississippi.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Several skirmishes but no major battles were fought in Florida.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The biggest was the Battle of Olustee in early 1864.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Pacific coast theater refers to military operations on the Pacific Ocean and in the states and territories west of the Continental Divide.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of 1864, Lincoln made Grant commander of all Union armies.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant made his headquarters with the Army of the Potomac and put Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] William Tecumseh Sherman in command of most of the western armies.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant understood the concept of total war and believed, along with Lincoln and Sherman, that only the utter defeat of Confederate forces and their economic base would end the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] This was total war not in killing civilians, but in injuring the Confederacy's capacity to produce and transport the supplies needed to continue the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman, at Grant's direction, seized provisions and destroyed homes, farms, and railroads, which Grant said "would otherwise have gone to the support of secession and rebellion.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant devised a coordinated strategy that would strike at the entire Confederacy from multiple directions.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Generals Meade and Benjamin Butler were ordered to move against Lee near Richmond, General Franz Sigel was to attack the Shenandoah Valley, General Sherman was to capture Atlanta and march to the Atlantic Ocean, Generals George Crook and William W.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Averell were to operate against railroad supply lines in West Virginia, and Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant's army set out on the Overland Campaign intending to draw Lee into a defense of Richmond, where they would attempt to pin down and destroy the Confederate army.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army first attempted to maneuver past Lee and fought several battles, notably at the Wilderness, Spotsylvania, and Cold Harbor.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] These resulted in heavy losses on both sides and forced Lee's Confederates to fall back repeatedly.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Yellow Tavern, the Confederates lost Jeb Stuart.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] An attempt to outflank Lee from the south failed under Butler, who was trapped inside the Bermuda Hundred river bend.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Each battle resulted in setbacks for the Union that mirrored those they had suffered under prior generals, though unlike them, Grant chose to fight on rather than retreat.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant was tenacious and kept pressing Lee's Army of Northern Virginia back to Richmond.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] While Lee was preparing for an attack on Richmond, Grant unexpectedly turned south to cross the James River and began the protracted Siege of Petersburg, where the two armies engaged in trench warfare for over nine months.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] To deny the Confederacy continued use of the Shenandoah Valley as a base from which to launch invasions of Maryland and the Washington area, and to threaten Lee's supply lines for his forces, Grant launched the Valley campaigns in May 1864.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Sigel were repelled at the Battle of New Market by Confederate Gen.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of New Market was the Confederacy's last major victory, and included a charge by teenage VMI cadets.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] After relieving Sigel, and following mixed performances by his successor, Grant finally found a commander, General Philip Sheridan, aggressive enough to prevail against the army of Maj.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] After a cautious start, Sheridan defeated Early in a series of battles in September and October 1864, including a decisive defeat at the Battle of Cedar Creek.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Sheridan then proceeded through that winter to destroy the agricultural base of the Shenandoah Valley, a strategy similar to the tactics Sherman later employed in Georgia.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Sherman maneuvered from Chattanooga to Atlanta, defeating Confederate Generals Joseph E.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The fall of Atlanta on September 2, 1864, guaranteed the reelection of Lincoln.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Hood left the Atlanta area to swing around and menace Sherman's supply lines and invade Tennessee in the Franklin–Nashville Campaign.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] John Schofield defeated Hood at the Battle of Franklin, and George H.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Thomas dealt Hood a massive defeat at the Battle of Nashville, effectively destroying Hood's army.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Leaving Atlanta, and his base of supplies, Sherman's army marched, with no destination set, laying waste to about 20 percent of the farms in Georgia on his March to the Sea.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] He reached the Atlantic at Savannah, Georgia, in December 1864.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman's army was followed by thousands of freed slaves; there were no major battles along the march.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman turned north through South Carolina and North Carolina in his Carolinas campaign, to approach the Confederate Virginia lines from the south, increasing the pressure on Lee's army.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lee's army, thinned by desertion and casualties, was now much smaller than Grant's.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] One last Confederate attempt to break the Union hold on Petersburg failed at the decisive Battle of Five Forks on April 1.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union now controlled the entire perimeter surrounding Richmond–Petersburg, completely cutting it off from the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Realizing the capital was now lost, Lee's army and the Confederate government were forced to evacuate.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate capital fell on April 2–3, to the Union XXV Corps, composed of black troops.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The remaining Confederate units fled west after a defeat at Sayler's Creek on April 6.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] front page celebrated Lee's surrender, headlining how Grant let Confederate officers retain their sidearms and "paroled" the Confederate officers and men.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] News of Lee's April 9 surrender reached this southern newspaper (Savannah, Georgia) on April 15—after the April 14 shooting of President Lincoln.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The article quotes Grant's terms of surrender.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lee did not intend to surrender, but planned to regroup at Appomattox Station, where supplies were to be waiting, and then continue the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Grant chased Lee and got in front of him, so that when Lee's army reached the village of Appomattox Court House, they were surrounded.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] After an initial battle, Lee decided the fight was hopeless, and surrendered his Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865, during a conference at the McLean House.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In an untraditional gesture and as a sign of Grant's respect and anticipation of peacefully restoring Confederate states to the Union, Lee was permitted to keep his sword and horse, Traveller.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] His men were paroled, and a chain of Confederate surrenders began.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] On April 14, 1865, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's vice president, Andrew Johnson, was unharmed, because his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, lost his nerve, so Johnson was immediately sworn in as president.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Confederate forces across the South surrendered, as news of Lee's surrender reached them.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] On April 26, the same day Sergeant Boston Corbett killed Booth at a tobacco barn, Johnston surrendered nearly 90,000 troops of the Army of Tennessee to Sherman at Bennett Place, near present-day Durham, North Carolina.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] It proved to be the largest surrender of Confederate forces.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] On May 4, all remaining Confederate forces in Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana east of the Mississippi, under the command of Lt.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate president Davis was captured in retreat at Irwinville, Georgia on May 10.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The final land battle was fought on May 13, 1865, at the Battle of Palmito Ranch in Texas.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Buckner, acting for Edmund Smith, signed a military convention surrendering Confederate forces in the Trans-Mississippi Department.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] This date is often cited by contemporaries and historians as the effective end date of the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] On June 2, with most of his troops having already gone home, a reluctant Kirby Smith had little choice but to sign the official surrender document.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] General Stand Watie became the last Confederate general to surrender his forces.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Gordon Granger announced General Order No.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] 3, bringing the Emancipation Proclamation into effect in Texas and freeing the last slaves of the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The anniversary of this date is now celebrated as Juneteenth.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The naval part of the war ended more slowly.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Britain finally responded on June 6, by transmitting a letter from Foreign Secretary John Russell, 1st Earl Russell, to the Lords of the Admiralty withdrawing rights to Confederate warships to enter British ports and waters.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] US Secretary of State Seward welcomed the withdrawal of concessions to the Confederates.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Finally, on October 18, Russell advised the Admiralty that the time specified in his June message had elapsed and "all measures of a restrictive nature on vessels of war of the United States in British ports, harbors, and waters, are now to be considered as at an end".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Nonetheless, the final Confederate surrender was in Liverpool, England where James Iredell Waddell, the captain of CSS *Shenandoah*, surrendered the cruiser to British authorities on November 6.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Legally, the war did not end until August 20, 1866, when President Johnson issued a proclamation that declared "that the said insurrection is at an end and that peace, order, tranquillity, and civil authority now exist in and throughout the whole of the United States of America".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The causes of the war, reasons for its outcome, and even its name are subjects of lingering contention.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The North and West grew wealthy while the once-rich South became poor for a century.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The national political power of the slaveowners and rich Southerners ended.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Historians are less sure about the results of postwar Reconstruction, especially regarding the second-class citizenship of the freedmen and their poverty.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Historians have debated whether the Confederacy could have won the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, argue Confederate victory was possible.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson argues that the North's advantage in population and resources made Northern victory likely, but not guaranteed.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] He argues that if the Confederacy had fought using unconventional tactics, it would have more easily been able to hold out long enough to exhaust the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Confederates did not need to invade and hold enemy territory to win, but only to fight a defensive war to convince the North the cost of winning was too high.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The North needed to conquer and hold vast stretches of enemy territory and defeat Confederate armies to win.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln was not a military dictator and could fight only as long as the American public supported the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy sought to win independence by outlasting Lincoln; however, after Atlanta fell and Lincoln defeated McClellan in the election of 1864, hope for a political victory for the South ended.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln had secured the support of the Republicans, War Democrats, border states, emancipated slaves, and the neutrality of Britain and France.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] By defeating the Democrats and McClellan, he defeated the Copperheads, who had wanted a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Some scholars argue the Union held an insurmountable long-term advantage over the Confederacy in industrial strength and population.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate actions, they argue, only delayed defeat.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] A minority view among historians is that the Confederacy lost because, as E.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Merton Coulter put it, "people did not will hard enough and long enough to win".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] However, most historians reject the argument.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, after reading thousands of letters written by Confederate soldiers, found strong patriotism that continued to the end; they truly believed they were fighting for freedom and liberty.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Even as the Confederacy was visibly collapsing in 1864–65, most Confederate soldiers were fighting hard.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Also important were Lincoln's eloquence in articulating the national purpose and his skill in keeping the border states committed to the Union cause.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation was an effective use of the president's war powers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate government failed to get Europe involved militarily.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Southern leaders needed to get European powers to help break the blockade the Union had created around Southern ports.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's naval blockade was 95 percent effective at stopping trade goods; as a result, imports and exports to the South declined significantly.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The abundance of European cotton and Britain's hostility to slavery, along with Lincoln's naval blockades, severely decreased any chance that Britain or France would enter the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Doyle has argued that the Union victory had a major impact on world history.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union victory energized popular democratic forces.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] A Confederate victory, on the other hand, would have meant a new birth of slavery, not of freedom.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Scholars have debated what the effects of the war were on political and economic power in the South.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The prevailing view is that the southern planter elite retained its powerful position in the South.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] However, a 2017 study challenges this, noting that while some Southern elites retained their economic status, the turmoil of the 1860s created greater opportunities for economic mobility in the South, than in the North.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Exact casualty figures were collected for the Union, but Confederate records were poorly kept, or lost in the chaos of defeat.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Thus, the casualty figures are imprecise and based on statistical extrapolation.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Neither side kept a tally of civilian deaths due to the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In the 19th century, the death toll had been estimated at a lower 620,000.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In 2011, the death toll was recalculated based on a 1% sample of census data, yielding approximately 750,000 soldier deaths, 20 percent higher than traditionally estimated, and possibly as high as 850,000.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The figure was recalculated to 698,000 soldier deaths in 2024 after examining newly available full census records.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Mortality rates among men were as high as 19 percent in Louisiana, and 16.6–16.7 percent in Georgia and South Carolina respectively.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The war resulted in at least 1,030,000 casualties (3 percent of the population), including an estimated 698,000 soldier deaths—two-thirds by disease.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Based on 1860 census figures, 8 percent of all white men aged 13–43 died in the war, including 6 percent in the North and 18 percent in the South.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] About 56,000 soldiers died in prison camps during the War.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] An estimated 60,000 soldiers lost limbs.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] As McPherson notes, the war's "cost in American lives was as great as in all of the nation's other wars combined through Vietnam".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In addition, there were 4,523 deaths in the Navy (2,112 in battle) and 460 in the Marines (148 in battle).
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The US Colored Troops made up 10 percent of the Union death toll—15 percent of Union deaths from disease and less than 3 percent of those killed in battle.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Losses among African Americans were high.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In the last year and a half and from all reported casualties, approximately 20 percent of all African Americans enrolled in the military died during the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Their mortality rate was significantly higher than white soldiers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] While 15 percent of US Volunteers and just 9 percent of white Regular Army troops died, 21 percent of US Colored Troops died.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] While the figures of 360,000 army deaths for the Union and 260,000 for the Confederacy remained commonly cited, they are incomplete.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] This often happened only days or weeks later.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Francis Amasa Walker, superintendent of the 1870 census, used census and surgeon general data to estimate a minimum of 500,000 Union military deaths and 350,000 Confederate military deaths, a total of 850,000 soldiers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] While Walker's estimates were originally dismissed because of the 1870 census's undercounting, it was later found that the census was only off by 6.5 percent and that the data Walker used would be roughly accurate.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Losses were far higher than during the war with Mexico, which saw roughly 13,000 American deaths, including fewer than two thousand killed in battle, between 1846 and 1848.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] One reason for the high number of battle deaths in the civil war was the continued use of tactics similar to those of the Napoleonic Wars, such as charging.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] With the advent of more accurate rifled barrels, Minié balls, and (near the end of the war for the Union) repeating firearms such as the Spencer repeating rifle and the Henry repeating rifle, soldiers were mowed down when standing in lines in the open.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] This led to the adoption of trench warfare, a style of fighting that defined much of World War I.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Deaths among former slaves has proven hard to estimate, due to the lack of reliable census data, though they were known to be considerable, as former slaves were set free or escaped in massive numbers in areas where the Union army did not have sufficient shelter, doctors, or food for them.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Professor Jim Downs states that tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of slaves died during the war from disease, starvation, or exposure, and that if these deaths are counted in the war's total, the death toll would exceed 1 million.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that during the war, of the equines killed, including horses, mules, donkeys and even confiscated children's ponies, over 32,600 of them belonged to the Union and 45,800 the Confederacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] However, other estimates place the total at 1,000,000.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that 544 Confederate flags were captured during the war by the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The flags were sent to the War Department in Washington.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Union flags captured by the Confederates were sent to Richmond.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Abolishing slavery was not a Union war goal from the outset but quickly became one.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln initially claimed that preserving the Union was the central goal.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In contrast, the South fought to preserve slavery.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] While not all Southerners saw themselves as fighting for slavery, most officers and over a third of the rank and file in Lee's army had close family ties to slavery.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] To Northerners, the motivation was primarily to preserve the Union, not to abolish slavery.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's decision to issue the Proclamation angered Peace Democrats ("Copperheads") and War Democrats, but energized most Republicans.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] By warning that free blacks would flood the North, Democrats made gains in the 1862 elections, but they did not gain control of Congress.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Republicans' counterargument that slavery was the mainstay of the enemy steadily gained support, with the Democrats losing decisively in the 1863 elections in the Northern state of Ohio, when they tried to resurrect anti-black sentiment.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation legally freed the slaves in states "in rebellion", but, as a practical matter, slavery for the 3.5 million black people in the South effectively ended in each area when Union armies arrived.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The last Confederate slaves were freed on June 19, 1865, celebrated as the modern holiday of Juneteenth.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Slaves in the border states and those in some former Confederate territory occupied before the Emancipation Proclamation were freed by state action or (on December 6, 1865) by the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation enabled African Americans, both free blacks and escaped slaves, to join the Union Army.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] About 190,000 volunteered, further enhancing the numerical advantage the Union armies enjoyed over the Confederates, who did not dare emulate the equivalent manpower source for fear of undermining the legitimacy of slavery.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] During the war, sentiment concerning slaves, enslavement, and emancipation in the United States was divided.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's fears of making slavery a war issue were based on a harsh reality: abolition did not enjoy wide support in the west, the territories, and the border states.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] In 1861, Lincoln worried that premature attempts at emancipation would mean the loss of the border states, and that "to lose Kentucky is nearly the same as to lose the whole game".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Copperheads and some War Democrats opposed emancipation, although the latter eventually accepted it as part of the total war needed to save the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln reversed attempts at emancipation by Secretary of War Simon Cameron and Generals John C.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont and David Hunter, in an effort to retain the loyalty of the border states and the War Democrats.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln warned the border states that a more radical type of emancipation would happen if they rejected his plan of gradual compensated emancipation and voluntary colonization.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] But compensated emancipation occurred only in the District of Columbia, where Congress had the power to enact it.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] When Lincoln told his cabinet about his proposed emancipation proclamation, which would apply to the states still in rebellion on January 1, 1863, Seward advised Lincoln to wait for a Union military victory before issuing it, because to do otherwise would seem like "our last shriek on the retreat".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Walter Stahr, however, writes, "There are contemporary sources, however, that suggest others were involved in the decision to delay", and Stahr quotes them.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] , who were fugitive slaves, including cooks, laundresses, laborers, teamsters, railroad repair crews, fled to the Union Army, but were not legally freed until the Emancipation Proclamation, which Lincoln signed on January 1, 1863, more than two years before the end of the Civil War.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] ; seen here are black and white teenaged soldiers who volunteered to fight for the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln laid the groundwork for public support in an open letter published in response to Horace Greeley's "The Prayer of Twenty Millions"; the letter stated that Lincoln's goal was to save the Union, and that, if he freed the slaves, it would be as a means to that end.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] He also had a meeting at the White House with five African American representatives on August 14, 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Arranging for a reporter to be present, he urged his visitors to agree to the voluntary colonization of black people.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's motive for both his letter to Greeley and his statement to the black visitors was apparently to make his forthcoming Emancipation Proclamation more palatable to racist white people.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] A Union victory in the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, provided Lincoln with an opportunity to issue the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, and the War Governors' Conference added support for the proclamation.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln issued his preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, 1862.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] It stated that slaves in all states in rebellion on January 1, 1863, would be free.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] He issued his final Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, keeping his promise.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Hodges, Lincoln explained his belief that "If slavery is not wrong, nothing is wrong....
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] And yet I have never understood that the Presidency conferred upon me an unrestricted right to act officially upon this judgment and feeling....
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's moderate approach succeeded in inducing the border states to remain in the Union and War Democrats to support the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The border states, which included Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware, and Union-controlled regions around New Orleans, Norfolk, Virginia, and elsewhere, were not covered by the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Nor was Tennessee, which had come under Union control.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri and Maryland abolished slavery on their own; Kentucky and Delaware did not.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Still, the proclamation did not enjoy universal support.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] It caused much unrest in what were then considered western states, where racist sentiments led to a great fear of abolition.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] There was some concern that the proclamation would lead to the secession of western states, and its issuance prompted the stationing of Union troops in Illinois in case of rebellion.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] Since the Emancipation Proclamation was based on the president's war powers, it applied only in territory held by Confederates at the time it was issued.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Proclamation became a symbol of the Union's growing commitment to add emancipation to the Union's definition of liberty.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation greatly reduced the Confederacy's hope of being recognized or otherwise aided by Britain or France.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p02] By late 1864, Lincoln was playing a leading role in getting the House of Representatives to vote for the Thirteenth Amendment, which mandated the ending of chattel slavery.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The war devastated the South and posed serious questions of how it would be reintegrated into the Union.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The war destroyed much of the South's wealth, in part because wealth held in enslaved people (at least $1,000 each for a healthy adult prior to the war) was wiped off the books.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] All accumulated investment in Confederate bonds was forfeited; most banks and railroads were bankrupt.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The income per person dropped to less than 40 percent of that of the North, and that lasted into the 20th century.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Southern influence in the federal government, previously considerable, was greatly diminished until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Reconstruction began during the war, with the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1863, and it continued until 1877.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] From the Union perspective, the goals of Reconstruction were to consolidate victory by reuniting the Union, to guarantee a "republican form of government" for the ex-Confederate states, and to permanently end slavery—and prevent semi-slavery status.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] President Johnson, who took office in April 1865, took a lenient approach and saw the achievement of the main war goals as realized in 1865, when each ex-rebel state repudiated secession and ratified the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Radical Republicans demanded proof that Confederate nationalism was dead and that the slaves were truly free.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] They overrode Johnson's vetoes of civil rights legislation, and the House impeached him, although the Senate did not convict him.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] In 1868 and 1872, the Republican candidate Grant won the presidency.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] In 1872, the "Liberal Republicans" argued that the war goals had been achieved and Reconstruction should end.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] They chose Horace Greeley to head a presidential ticket in 1872 but were decisively defeated.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] In 1874, Democrats, primarily Southern, took control of Congress and opposed further reconstruction.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The Compromise of 1877 closed with a national consensus, except on the part of former slaves, that the war had finally ended.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] With the withdrawal of federal troops, however, white men retook control of every Southern legislature, and the Jim Crow era of disenfranchisement and legal segregation was ushered in.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The war had a demonstrable impact on American politics.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Many veterans on both sides were elected to political office, including five US presidents: Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Garfield, Benjamin Harrison, and William McKinley.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The war is a central event in American collective memory.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] There are innumerable statues, commemorations, books, and archival collections.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The memory includes the home front, military affairs, the treatment of soldiers, both living and dead, in the war's aftermath, depictions of the war in literature and art, evaluations of heroes and villains, and considerations of the moral and political lessons of the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The last theme includes moral evaluations of racism and slavery, heroism and cowardice in combat and behind the lines, and issues of democracy and minority rights, as well as the notion of an "Empire of Liberty" influencing the world.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Historians have paid great attention to the causes of the war as well as to the war itself.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Military history has developed outside as well as inside academia, leading to a proliferation of studies by non-scholars who nevertheless are familiar with the primary sources and pay close attention to battles and campaigns and who write for the general public.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Practically every major figure in the war, both North and South, has had a serious biographical study.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Even the name used for the conflict has been controversial, with many names used for it.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] During and immediately after the war, Northern historians often used a term like "War of the Rebellion".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Writers in rebel states often referred to the "War for Southern Independence".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Some Southerners have described it as the "War of Northern Aggression".
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The memory of the war in the white South crystallized in the myth of the "Lost Cause": that the Confederate cause was just and heroic.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The myth shaped regional identity and race relations for generations.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan notes that the Lost Cause was expressly a rationalization, a cover-up to vindicate the name and fame of those in rebellion.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Some claims revolve around the insignificance of slavery as a cause; some appeals highlight cultural differences between North and South; the military conflict by Confederate actors is idealized; in any case, secession was said to be lawful.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan argues that the adoption of the Lost Cause perspective facilitated the reunification of the North and the South while excusing the "virulent racism" of the 19th century, sacrificing black American progress to white man's reunification.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] He also deems the Lost Cause "a caricature of the truth.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] This caricature wholly misrepresents and distorts the facts of the matter" in every instance.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The Lost Cause myth was formalized by Charles A.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Beard, whose *The Rise of American Civilization* (1927) spawned Beardian historiography.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The Beards downplayed slavery, abolitionism, and issues of morality.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Though this interpretation was abandoned by the Beards in the 1940s, and by historians generally by the 1950s, Beardian themes still echo among Lost Cause writers.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The first efforts at Civil War battlefield preservation and memorialization came during the war, with the establishment of National Cemeteries at Gettysburg, Mill Springs and Chattanooga.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Soldiers began erecting markers on battlefields beginning with the First Battle of Bull Run in 1861.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The oldest surviving monument is the Hazen Brigade Monument near Murfreesboro in Central Tennessee, built in the summer of 1863 by soldiers in Union Col.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Hazen's brigade to mark the spot where they buried their dead, following the Battle of Stones River.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The Shiloh National Military Park was established in 1894 in Shiloh, Tennessee, followed by the Gettysburg National Military Park in 1895, and Vicksburg National Military Park in 1899.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] In 1933, these five parks and other national monuments were transferred to the National Park Service.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Chief among modern efforts to preserve Civil War sites has been the American Battlefield Trust, with more than 130 battlefields in 24 states.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The five major battlefield parks operated by the National Park Service had a combined 3 million visitors in 2018, down 70% from 10 million in 1970.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War has been commemorated in many ways, ranging from the reenactment of battles, to statues and memorial halls being erected, to films, and to stamps and coins with Civil War themes being issued, all of which helped to shape public memory.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] These commemorations occurred in greater numbers on the 100th and 150th anniversaries of the war.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Hollywood's take on the war has been especially influential in shaping public memory, as in such film classics as *The Birth of a Nation* (1915), *Gone with the Wind* (1939), and *Lincoln* (2012).
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Ken Burns's PBS television series *The Civil War* (1990) is well-remembered, though criticized for its historical inaccuracy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Technological innovations during the war had a great impact on 19th-century science.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The war was an early example of an "industrial war", in which technological might is used to achieve military supremacy.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] New inventions, such as the train and telegraph, delivered soldiers, supplies and messages at a time when horses had been the fastest way to travel.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] It was also in this war that aerial warfare, in the form of reconnaissance balloons, was first used.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] It saw the first action involving steam-powered ironclad warships in naval warfare history.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] Repeating firearms such as the Henry rifle, Spencer repeating rifle, Colt revolving rifle, Triplett & Scott carbine and others, first appeared during the Civil War; they were a revolutionary invention that would soon replace muzzle-loading and single-shot firearms.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The war saw the first appearances of rapid-firing weapons and machine guns such as the Agar gun and Gatling gun.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War is one of the most studied events in American history, and the collection of cultural works around it is enormous.
[src:floating-battery/american-civil-war-p03] This section gives an abbreviated overview of the most notable works.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria was considered the foremost naval leader in Europe at his time.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] From 1528, he served as Holy Roman Emperor Charles V's grand admiral in the Mediterranean, as well as his main shipbuilder along with Álvaro de Bazán the Elder, while also acting as a privateer with the ships he owned in order to increase his own wealth.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Although he had mixed success against the power of the Ottoman admirals, his fleet helped secure the imperial naval lines between Spain and Italy.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He also played a role in the development of amphibious warfare by the Spanish and Italian navies.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] As a citizen of Genoa, Doria used his relationship with Charles V to both protect the republic's independence and exercise a predominant influence in its councils.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He refused official charges, accepting only the title of Father of the Fatherland, and instead ruled the republic as an economic and military player.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Under his reforms, the Doge's office was reduced to two years instead of being elected for life, while plebeians were declared ineligible, and the appointment was entrusted to the members of the great and the little councils.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] His constitutional reforms would last until the end of the republic in 1797.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] His posterior historical reputation became influenced by the lens of his Venetian rivals, which accused him of unstrategic and duplicitous conduct in battle.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Even then, several ships in the next centuries were named in his honour, the most famous being the Italian passenger liner SS *Andrea Doria*, launched in 1951, which sank following a collision in 1956.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria was born at Oneglia from the ancient Genoese family the Doria di Oneglia, a branch of the noble Doria family, who played a major role in the history of the Republic since the 12th century.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] His parents were related: Ceva Doria, co-lord of Oneglia, and Caracosa Doria, of the Doria di Dolceacqua branch.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Orphaned at an early age, he became a soldier of fortune, serving first in the papal guard and then under various Italian princes.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He soon gained enough renown for Gonzalo Fernández de Córdoba, the premier general of the age, to tempt him to join him.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In 1503, he fought in Corsica in the service of the Genoese Navy, at that time under French vassalage.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] However, after the Battle of Ravenna of 1512, he turned against the Francophile government of Genoa represented by Gian Fregoso.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] At age 46, despite having no previous naval experience, Doria was appointed admiral and took it upon himself to reorganize the existing Genoese fleet.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] A French invasion of Genoa forced him and his fleet to escape to La Spezia.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] With the French defeat in Novara the following year, Doria returned and conquered the local French garrison in Briglia, expelled them from Genoa and helped Ottaviano Fregoso to become the new Doge.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria also scoured the Mediterranean in command of the Genoese fleet, waging war on the Turks and the Barbary pirates.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] When a fleet led by the brothers Aruj and Hayreddin Barbarossa, coming from a failed siege of the Spanish port of Béjaïa, captured a Genoese ship in 1512, Doria attacked the brothers' base in La Goulette with twelve galleys, sacking the place and destroying the ships in port.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In the meanwhile, however, Genoa was recaptured by the French, as a new change of tide in Marignano forced Fregoso to pledge Genoa to King Francis I of France in 1515.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria focused in his actions against Muslims, defeated another Turk fleet led by Caid Ali or Cadolin at Pianosa in 1519, capturing his ships for his own fleet.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In 1522, during the Italian War between France and the empire of Charles V, King of Spain and Holy Roman Emperor, Genoa was conquered and sacked by imperial troops under the command of Prospero Colonna and Fernando d'Ávalos, forcing Doria to escape with the fleet again.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Taking refuge in Monaco, he helped the French defend Marseille in 1524, but the war came to an abrupt end when Francis I was captured by the imperial army in Pavia in 1525.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria prepared a plan to rescue him, but Francis ordered him to refrain.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria then clashed with Francis' regent, Anne de Montmorency, and abandoned French service, forming a naval mercenary fleet.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In June 1526, at the head of thirteen ships, he crossed paths again with Hayreddin Barbarossa in the coast of Civitavecchia, defeating the Turk and capturing fifteen of his sixteen vessels, with Barbarossa managing to escape in his flagship alone.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] However, Doria ended up siding with France again when Pope Clement VII formed the League of Cognac to oppose Charles V, for which Doria was hired to command their armada while Giovanni delle Bande Nere did the same in their land army.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria defeated a bigger Spanish fleet in Corsica and planned to conquer Genoa, still under imperial rule, but it was never carried on.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] With Giovanni's death in action and the sack of Rome by mutinied imperial troops, the situation worsened for the League of Cognac, who depended on Doria more than ever.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In 1528, the League's armada, under the command of Doria and his nephew, Filippino Doria, crushed a Spanish fleet on 28 April 1528 at the Battle of Capo d'Orso, capturing the enemy commanders Alfonso d'Avalos and Ascanio Colonna.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] However, Andrea became dissatisfied with his treatment at the hands of Francis, who was mean about payment and replaced Doria for the French admiral Antoine de La Rochefoucauld.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Meanwhile, d'Avalos capitalized on the chance to try to convince Doria to switch sides, with Doria refusing to hand d'Avalos and Colonna to Francis as the king asked.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Charles V and Doria exchanged letters, and although Francis found out about it and attempted to compensate the Genoese, the latter deserted the French for the emperor on June 1528.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Without Doria's fleet, the League collapsed.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The Genoese lifted the siege of Naples, chasing La Rochefoucauld to Provence and capturing four of his ships.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In September, Doria and his forces drove the French out of Genoa and were triumphantly received by the city.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Charles appointed him grand admiral, prince of Melfi and Marquis of Tursi in reward for his services.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He found Doria an invaluable ally in the wars with Francis I, and through him extended his domination over the whole of Italy.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He continued to serve the emperor in various wars, in which he was generally successful and always active.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria reformed the constitution in an aristocratic sense, eliminating the factions that had plagued the republic in the past centuries, and constituted a new oligarchic form of government composed of the city's principal aristocratic families, creating 28 Alberghi or "clans".
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The 28 Alberghi that formed this new ruling class included the Cybo, Doria, Fieschi, Giustiniani, Grimaldi, Imperiale, Pallavicino, and Spinola families.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He refused offers to take the lordship of Genoa and even the dogeship, but accepted the position of perpetual censor and the title of Father of the Fatherland (*Liberator et Pater Patriae*).
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He was still the de facto ruler of Genoa due to his economic and military power, and exercised undisputed influence in the councils of the republic until his death.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The title "censor" in this context was modelled on its meaning in the Roman Republic, *i.e.*, a highly respected senior public official (see Roman censor), rather than its modern meaning having to do with censorship.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He was given two palaces and many privileges.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He established himself in his newly renovated villa in Fassolo, a Renaissance masterpiece known as Villa del Principe, in an area just outside the now demolished Porta di San Tomaso, where he resided until his death.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] To protect the restored republic from future foreign attacks, Doria sponsored the construction of a new city wall, which was built in the third decade of the sixteenth century, on a design by the military engineer Giovanni Maria Olgiati.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] This new city wall actually followed the path of the previous 14th-century walls but replaced the old square-plan towers and walls with new curtain-shaped curtain walls and triangular bastions.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Actions against the Ottomans and Barbary pirates occupied again much of Doria's time.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In 1529, Spanish captain Rodrigo de Portundo was defeated by Aydın Reis, lieutenant of Hayreddin Barbarossa.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Finding out Barbarossa had Cádiz on his sights, Doria launched an attack on Cherchell, where Barbarossa was planning to supply his fleet.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In summer 1532, in response to the Turk invasion of Hungary in April, Andrea attacked the Ottoman positions in the Aegean Sea with a Spanish-Genoese fleet of 48 galleys and 35 vessels.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He headed to Morea, capturing Coron by way of a novel system of cannons and ladders in his masts to assault the coastal bulwark.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria followed by taking and sacking Patras, destroying fortresses around the Gulf of Corinth.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria returned to Genoa with booty of 60,000 ducats, having helped force the Ottomans to abort a possible conquest of Hungary.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The Ottomans attempted to recover Coron the following year with a 110-ship armada captained by Lütfi Pasha.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria gathered 27 galleys and 30 ships in Messina and lifted the siege.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria forced Lufti to withdraw despite having a much smaller fleet, outmaneuvering the Turks with his galleys despite the absence of wind having becalmed his other ships, and losing only three galleys in the battle.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The relief of Coron would be called by Edmond Jurien de La Gravière one of the most skillful naval operations of the 16th century.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Barbarossa, now turned into grand admiral of the Ottoman Empire, launched his own offensive from Constantinople with 80 galleys and French support, sacking around Naples and Sicily.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In 1535, Charles V called for the conquest of Tunis, which Barbarossa had just conquered and made his base.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The fleet, with Doria sharing main command with Bazán the Elder, succeeded in taking Tunis and capturing Barbarossa's entire fleet, although the corsair managed to escape.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria followed Barbarossa to Bona, which the Genoese stormed, but Barbarossa had fled and taken refuge in Algiers.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Charles intended to continue the campaign taking Algiers next, but the approaching autumn weather prevented it.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] After the death of Francesco I Sforza in 1535, Charles V and Francis I clashed again for the succession of the Duchy of Milan.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria was vital for the emperor to secure the friendship of the Médicis of Florence, favoring the ascension of Cosimo I.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria and Bazán the Elder captured cities along the French Riviera, although stopping in Marseille.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Shortly after, Barbarossa attacked and sacked the Balearic Islands with 27 galleasses he gathered in Algiers, leading Doria to give him chase unsuccessfully with 30 galleys, with orders of Charles V to bring the Turk privateer dead or alive.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In a shocking move, Francis allied with the Ottomans in 1536, installing Barbarossa with a Franco-Turk fleet in Marseille, although the defenses built by Doria dissuaded them from trying to take Genoa.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In April 1537, Barbarossa appeared in front of Italy with 170 ships, but he had come to negotiate, and through a Spanish prisoner he proposed the emperor a possible desertion of the Ottoman Empire, citing his enmity with Lütfi and the political turmoil after the killing of Pargalı Ibrahim Pasha.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In July, due to the outbreak of the Ottoman–Venetian War, Doria sailed off at the head of 28 galleys from Messina.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria retreated to Messina, where being unable to confront directly the 320-ship Ottoman armada, he was forced to hear how Barbarossa sacked Apulia and the Ottomans boasted they might be able to choose their own Pope some day.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria harassed the Ottoman captured a fleet of 10 Ottoman supply ships, after which he defeated Ali Celebi and his 12 galleys in the Battle of Antipaxos.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] After the battle, he managed to involve the Venetians with the war, leading to the Ottomans to depart Apulia and start the siege of the Venetian colony of Corfu.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] After finally gathering 100 ships, Doria marched to relieve it, but the Ottomans had lifted it themselves.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In February 1538, Pope Paul III called for peace among the Christians and the formation of a Holy League (comprising the Papal States, Spain, the Holy Roman Empire, the Republic of Venice, and the Maltese Knights) against the Turks.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Although Francis did not join, the Italian War came to its end with the Truce of Nice, and he accepted to break his alliance with the Ottomans.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In 1538, being given command of the Holy League, Doria sailed off with 80 Venetian galleys, 36 from the Vatican States, 30 from Spain, as well as 50 naus, with the goal to seek the encounter with Barbarossa's fleet and defeat him.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He tracked Barbarossa and his lieutenants, which included Sinan, Salah and Dragut or Turgut Reis, to the strait of Corinth, where he blockaded them.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] However, the Christian fleet was routed in unclear circumstances in the subsequent Battle of Preveza in September 1538.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Venetian sources, which became the mainstream account, accused Doria of lack of initiative, which might have obeyed to Spain and Genoa being unwilling to commit themselves in defense of the politically distant Venice, not any less to the fact that Doria owned many of the ships employed.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Imperial sources instead had Doria disobeyed by the Venetians out of political rivalry in a critical moment, forcing him to forfeit the battle.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] This victory secured Turkish dominance over the eastern Mediterranean for the next 33 years, until the Battle of Lepanto in 1571.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] To compensate the defeat, they captured Castelnuovo, but Charles and Venice argued about who would keep the place, causing the practical disbandment of the Holy League.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The garrison, initially conceived as the beachhead of an invasion of the Ottoman Balkans, was besieged and defeated by Barbarossa in the notorious Siege of Castelnuovo, although with enormous cost for the Turks.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In 1540, he launched a great operation to capture Dragut, the most eminent Turkish captain other than Babarossa, which was arrested by his nephew Giannettino Doria in a big victory in the Battle of Girolata.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Andrea had him as a galley slave in his flagship during four years.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Meanwhile, Andrea conquered multiple remaining Ottoman strongholds in Africa, including Monastir, Sousse and Hammamet.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Around this time, a usual partner to Doria, Bernardino de Mendoza, achieved another victory over Ottoman privateers in the Battle of Alborán.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Andrea, Giannettino and Mendoza were recruited by Charles V in 1541 to launch an expedition to Algiers, a new attempt to capture Barbarossa.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria tried to warn the emperor of the terrible timing of the move, as it was autumn and the Mediterranean weather was dangerous, but he was not heeded, and the Genoese reluctantly accepted to participate anyways.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The result was a fiasco, as a storm disintegrated he imperial fleet, although the Dorias managed to secure the retreat of a large part of the fleet, taking a large effort to reorganize the other Genoese captains.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In 1542, the now allied French and Ottomans sacked Nice, being chased away by Doria, who captured four ships.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In May, Hayreddin Barbarossa attacked Reggio with 110 galleys, linking with the French fleet in Marseille, where command was shared with Francis of Bourbon.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Again, Barbarossa and Bourbon conquered and sacked Nice, except by its citadel, and retreated with the arrival of Doria, who disembarked a land army led by Alfonso d'Avalos in Villefranche.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Nice was recovered, while the Franco-Turk fleet moved to Antibes.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Meanwhile, Bazán the Elder destroyed the French Atlantic fleet in Muros Bay, where his son Álvaro de Bazán was present.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] To great outrage of Christendom, in 1544 Doria freed Dragut in exchange for a rich rescue of 3,000 ducats paid by Barbarossa, who had also threatened with blockading Genoa.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria was probably trying to gain the Ottomans' sympathy in the case one of his own relatives was captured, although he eventually repented his decision due to Dragut's many future successes.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The Genoese then advised d'Avalos not to look for a direct battle against the French, but due to the bad state of their relationship, d'Avalos rebuked him and did it nonetheless, being defeated in Ceresole.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria helped impeding the French from capitalizing on the chance, attacking the French positions in the coast.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] After the Peace of Crépy between Francis and Charles in 1544, Doria hoped to end his days in quiet.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] However, his great wealth and power, as well as the arrogance of his nephew and heir Giannettino Doria, had made him many enemies, and in 1547 the Fieschi conspiracy to dislodge his family from power took place.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Giannettino was killed, but the conspirators were defeated, and Doria showed great vindictiveness in punishing them, seizing many of their fiefs for himself.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He was also implicated in the murder of Pier Luigi Farnese, duke of Parma and Piacenza, who had helped Fieschi.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Imperial governor Ferrante Gonzaga suggested to hold a Spanish garrison in Genoa, but Doria vetoed it for the sake of the city's independence.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Other conspiracies followed, of which the most important was that of Giulio Cybo (1548), but all failed.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Although Doria was ambitious and harsh, he was a patriot and successfully opposed Emperor Charles's repeated attempts to have a citadel built in Genoa and garrisoned by Spaniards; neither blandishments nor threats could win him over to the scheme.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Nor did age lessen his energy, for in 1550, aged 84, he again put to sea to confront the Muslim armadas, as although Barbarossa had retired in 1545, Dragut and the Barbary pirates continued being a threat.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria and Mendoza captured Mahdia, which Dragut had recently conquered as his headquarters.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In the citadel they captured Hesar, a nephew to Dragut himself.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria reinforced the garrison the next year, after which he found and chased Turgut and his 20 galleys to Djerba, blockading the privateer with few ships in an inlet.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Dragut still escaped, digging a channel and dragging his ships overland to it.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria had to be content with sacking Djerba.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] In 1552, a 100-galley Ottoman fleet under the command of Dragut ambushed 40 Spanish and Genoese transport galleys commanded by Doria in the Ponza, although Doria managed to escape losing only seven of them.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The war between France and the Empire having broken out once more, the French invaded Corsica, then administered by the Genoese Bank of Saint George.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria was again summoned, and he spent two years (1553–1555) on the island fighting the French with varying fortune.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He returned to Genoa for good in 1555, now with Charles' successor Philip II.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Andrea Doria left his estates to Giovanni Andrea.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The family of Doria-Pamphili-Landi is descended from Giovanni Andrea Doria and bears his title of Prince of Melfi.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Historian Henry Kamen regarded Doria as the most distinguished admiral of his time, an opinion echoed by others.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Tucker and others considered him the best Christian admiral of his time, with successes in both land and sea.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] According to Stanley Lane-Poole, "no name struck such terror into the hearts of the Turks." His leadership brought Genoa both fortune and independence within the Habsburg sphere of power, which won him widespread popularity in the city.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria was Charles V's main admiral along with Álvaro de Bazán the Elder and Bernardino de Mendoza.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] The three played roles in the establishment of the Spanish treasure fleet system, with Doria and Bazán the Elder additionally becoming the main shipbuilders of Charles' navies.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria also participated in the evolution of amphibious warfare led by Spanish and Italians, based in direct assaults with marine infantry and artillery.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Despite his mixed success against the still dominant Ottoman navy, he largely succeeded in keeping the Imperial naval lines open between Spain and Italy.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] He was only rivaled by his enemy Barbarossa, whose relationship with Hamilton Currey described as, "with them the ebb and flow of conquest and defeat alternated... great as was the one, it cannot be said that he was greater than the other".
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] It has been speculated the two maintained secret agreements to let each other escape, as Barbarossa was in usual negotiations with Charles V to potentially desert to imperial service.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria is sometimes considered a privateer, not unlike Barbarossa himself, as he used his private fleet to increase his own wealth.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Doria's international reputation suffered with the fiasco of Preveza against Barbarossa.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Spanish-Imperial sources accused the Venetians of betraying Doria, while the Venetians accused Doria of sabotaging the battle, with the latter version becoming predominant in historiography due to its quickness and vigor.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Venetians colored Doria as a strong admiral, but also indecisive in his tactics and adverse to risk the fleets he owned, which was echoed by even Spanish chroniclers like Prudencio de Sandoval.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Despite this, he retained the favor of Charles V and Philip II to his death.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] Several ships were named in his honour since.
[src:floating-battery/andrea-doria] A painted sheepskin for *The Magnificent and Excellent Andrea Doria* hangs at The Breakers in Newport, Rhode Island, US.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] The **Anglo-Spanish War of 1727–1729** was a limited war that took place between Great Britain and Spain during the late 1720s, and consisted of a failed Spanish attempt to capture Gibraltar and an unsuccessful British Blockade of Porto Bello with a high British death toll.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] It eventually ended with a return to the previous status quo ante bellum following the Treaty of Seville.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] After the Treaty of Vienna in 1725, Spain had the support of Austria and thought the time to be right to try to recapture Gibraltar.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] In reaction, Britain signed the Treaty of Hanover with France and Prussia.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] Some historians put the beginning of the war in 1726, the year in which the Anglo-Spanish relation was already very tense.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] A British fleet was sent to the Spanish West Indies to disturb Spanish shipping without actually starting a war.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] Britain had tried to use its naval power early in the dispute, by blockading Porto Bello in Panama but the attempt proved a disaster, in which 4,000 men were lost to disease.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] The main objective of the blockade had been to prevent Spanish galleons leaving and sailing for Spain, but the blockade failed to accomplish this - and eventually withdrew.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] On 11 February 1727 Spain, under command of the Marquis de las Torres and supervision of Chief Engineer of the Spanish Royal Engineer Corps Marquis of Verboom, laid siege to the city (*Thirteenth Siege of Gibraltar*).
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] Depending on the sources, Spanish troops were between 12,000 and 25,000.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] British defenders were 1,500 at the beginning of the siege, increasing up to about 5,000 by troops brought from overseas by a fleet commanded by Charles Wager.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] After a four-month siege, with several unsuccessful and costly attempts, Spanish troops gave up and retired on 12 June.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] Spain had lost over 1,400 men while the British had suffered around 300 casualties.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] The Spanish had expected material help from the Austrians promised under the Treaty of Vienna, but they received little.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] They had been outmaneuvered by British diplomats, who had concluded a secret deal with the Austrians to prevent them intervening.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] No more hostilities took place and a truce was declared in February 1728, with a preliminary agreement of issues at the March Convention of El Pardo and the Congress of Soissons.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] The final peace, that confirmed the status-quo, was concluded in the 1729 Treaty of Seville.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] Many of the outstanding issues between the two states had not been resolved, and a decade later the War of Jenkins' Ear broke out between them.
[src:floating-battery/anglo-spanish-war-1727-1729] Britain emerged from the conflict by forming a very strong alliance with Austria, that lasted until 1756.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] An **arsenal ship** is a naval concept for a warship intended to serve as a floating missile launcher platform with as many as five hundred vertical launch bays for large-sized guided missiles, most likely cruise missiles.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] In current U.S. naval thinking, such a ship would initially be controlled manually by an Aegis Cruiser, although plans that have long since been scrapped included control by AEW&C aircraft such as the E-2 Hawkeye and E-3 Sentry.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] Originally proposed by VADM Joseph Metcalf, DCNO Surface Warfare, as a component of the "Surface Combatants of the 21st Century" initiative in the mid-1980s.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] Navy in 1996, the arsenal ship had funding problems, with the United States Congress canceling some funding, and the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) providing some funding to individual contractors for prototypes.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] Some concept artwork of the Arsenal Ship was produced, with some images bearing the number "72", possibly hinting at an intent to classify the arsenal ships as a battleship, since the last battleship ordered (but never built) was USS *Louisiana* (BB-71).
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] The arsenal ship would have a small crew and as many as 500 vertical launch tubes for missiles to provide ship-to-shore bombardment for invading troops.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] The Navy calculated a $450 million price for the arsenal ship, but Congress scrapped funding for the project in 1998.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] In 2013, Huntington Ingalls Industries revived the idea when it proposed a Flight II version of the LPD-17 hull with a variant carrying up to 288 VLS cells for the ballistic missile defense and precision strike missions.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] China has conducted studies and tested models of partially and completely submersible arsenal ship concepts.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] South Korea is also planning to deploy three arsenal ships by the late 2020s.
[src:floating-battery/arsenal-ship] These South Korean arsenal ships are designated "Joint Strike Ships", or "JSS".
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The **Baltic Sea** is an arm of the Atlantic Ocean that is enclosed by the countries of Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Germany, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Russia, Sweden, and the North and Central European Plain regions.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It is the world's largest brackish water basin.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The sea stretches from 53°N to 66°N latitude and from 10°E to 30°E longitude.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It is a shelf sea and marginal sea of the Atlantic with limited water exchange between the two, making it an inland sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea drains through the Danish Straits into the Kattegat by way of the Øresund, Great Belt and Little Belt.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It includes the Gulf of Bothnia (divided into the Bothnian Bay and the Bothnian Sea), the Gulf of Finland, the Gulf of Riga and the Bay of Gdańsk.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The "Baltic Proper" is bordered on its northern edge, at latitude 60°N, by Åland and the Gulf of Bothnia, on its northeastern edge by the Gulf of Finland, on its eastern edge by the Gulf of Riga, and in the west by the Swedish part of the southern Scandinavian Peninsula.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea is connected by artificial waterways to the White Sea via the White Sea–Baltic Canal and to the German Bight of the North Sea via the Kiel Canal.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The narrowest part of Little Belt is the "Middelfart Sund" near Middelfart.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Geographers widely agree that the preferred physical border between the Baltic and North Seas is the Langelandsbælt (the southern part of the Great Belt strait near Langeland) and the Drogden-Sill strait.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Drogden Sill is situated north of Køge Bugt and connects Dragør in the south of Copenhagen to Malmö; it is used by the Øresund Bridge, including the *Drogden Tunnel*.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] By this definition, the Danish Straits is part of the entrance, but the Bay of Mecklenburg and the Bay of Kiel are parts of the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Another usual border is the line between Falsterbo, Sweden, and Stevns Klint, Denmark, as this is the southern border of Øresund.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It is also the border between the shallow southern Øresund (with a typical depth of 5–10 meters only) and notably deeper water.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Drogden Sill (depth of 7 m (23 ft)) sets a limit to Øresund and Darss Sill (depth of 18 m (59 ft)), and a limit to the Belt Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The shallow sills are obstacles to the flow of heavy salt water from the Kattegat into the basins around Bornholm and Gotland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Kattegat and the southwestern Baltic Sea are well oxygenated and have a rich biology.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The remainder of the Sea is brackish, poor in oxygen, and in species.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Thus, statistically, the more of the entrance that is included in its definition, the healthier the Baltic appears; conversely, the more narrowly it is defined, the more endangered its biology appears.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The precise origin of the name is unknown.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Tacitus called it the Suebic Sea, Latin: *Mare Suebicum* after the Germanic people of the Suebi, and Ptolemy *Sarmatian Ocean* after the Sarmatians, but the first to name it the *Baltic Sea* (Medieval Latin: *Mare Balticum*) was the eleventh-century German chronicler Adam of Bremen.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It might be connected to the Germanic word *belt*, a name used for two of the Danish Straits, the Belts, while others claim it to be directly derived from the source of the Germanic word, Latin *balteus* "belt".
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Adam of Bremen himself compared the sea with a belt, stating that it is so named because it stretches through the land as a belt (*Balticus, eo quod in modum baltei longo tractu per Scithicas regiones tendatur usque in Greciam*).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] He might also have been influenced by the name of a legendary island mentioned in the *Natural History* of Pliny the Elder.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Pliny mentions an island named *Baltia* (or *Balcia*) with reference to accounts of Pytheas and Xenophon.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It is possible that Pliny refers to an island named Basilia ("the royal") in *On the Ocean* by Pytheas.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] *Baltia* also might be derived from "belt", and therein mean "near belt of sea, strait".
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Others have suggested that the name of the island originates from the Proto-Indo-European root **bʰel* meaning "white, fair", which may echo the naming of seas after colours relating to the cardinal points (as per Black Sea and Red Sea).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] This **bʰel* root and basic meaning were retained in Lithuanian (as *baltas*), Latvian (as *balts*) and Slavic (as *bely*).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] On this basis, a related hypothesis holds that the name originated from this Indo-European root via a Baltic language such as Lithuanian.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Yet another explanation is that the name originally meant "enclosed sea, bay" as opposed to open sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the Middle Ages the sea was known by a variety of names.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The name Baltic Sea became dominant after 1600.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Usage of *Baltic* and similar terms to denote the region east of the sea started only in the 19th century.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea was known in ancient Latin language sources as *Mare Suebicum* or even *Mare Germanicum*.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] At the time of the Roman Empire, the Baltic Sea was known as the *Mare Suebicum* or *Mare Sarmaticum*.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Tacitus in his AD 98 *Agricola* and *Germania* described the Mare Suebicum, named for the Suebi tribe, during the spring months, as a brackish sea where the ice broke apart and chunks floated about.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Suebi eventually migrated southwest to temporarily reside in the Rhineland area of modern Germany, where their name survives in the historic region known as Swabia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Jordanes called it the *Germanic Sea* in his work, the *Getica*.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the early Middle Ages, Norse (Scandinavian) merchants built a trade empire all around the Baltic.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Later, the Norse fought for control of the Baltic against Wendish tribes dwelling on the southern shore.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Norse also used the rivers of Russia for trade routes, finding their way eventually to the Black Sea and southern Russia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] This Norse-dominated period is referred to as the Viking Age.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Since the Viking Age, the Scandinavians have referred to the Baltic Sea as *Austmarr* ("Eastern Sea").
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] "Eastern Sea", appears in the *Heimskringla* and *Eystra salt* appears in *Sörla þáttr*.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Saxo Grammaticus recorded in *Gesta Danorum* an older name, *Gandvik*, *-vik* being Old Norse for "bay", which implies that the Vikings correctly regarded it as an inlet of the sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Another form of the name, "Grandvik", attested in at least one English translation of *Gesta Danorum*, is likely to be a misspelling.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In addition to fish the sea also provides amber, especially from its southern shores within today's borders of Poland, Russia and Lithuania.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] First mentions of amber deposits on the South Coast of the Baltic Sea date back to the 12th century.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The bordering countries have also traditionally exported lumber, wood tar, flax, hemp and furs by ship across the Baltic.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Sweden had from early medieval times exported iron and silver mined there, while Poland had and still has extensive salt mines.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Thus, the Baltic Sea has long been crossed by much merchant shipping.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The lands on the Baltic's eastern shore were among the last in Europe to be converted to Christianity.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] This finally happened during the Northern Crusades: Finland in the twelfth century by Swedes, and what are now Estonia and Latvia in the early thirteenth century by Danes and Germans (Livonian Brothers of the Sword).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Teutonic Order gained control over parts of the southern and eastern shore of the Baltic Sea, where they set up their monastic state.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Lithuania was the last European state to convert to Christianity.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the period between the 8th and 14th centuries, there was much piracy in the Baltic from the coasts of Pomerania and Prussia, and the Victual Brothers held Gotland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Starting in the 11th century, the southern and eastern shores of the Baltic were settled by migrants mainly from Germany, a movement called the *Ostsiedlung* ("east settling").
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Other settlers were from the Netherlands, Denmark, and Scotland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Polabian Slavs were gradually assimilated by the Germans.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Denmark gradually gained control over a large portion of the Baltic coast, until it lost many of its possessions after being defeated in the 1227 Battle of Bornhöved.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Between the 13th and 17th centuries the Baltic Sea was, depending on the period, dominated by the Netherlands, Germany, Sweden and Russia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the 13th to 16th centuries, the strongest economic force in Northern Europe was the Hanseatic League, a federation of merchant cities around the Baltic Sea and the North Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the sixteenth and early seventeenth centuries, Poland, Denmark, and Sweden fought wars for *Dominium maris baltici* ("Lordship over the Baltic Sea").
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Eventually, it was Sweden that virtually encompassed the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In Sweden, the sea was then referred to as *Mare Nostrum Balticum* ("Our Baltic Sea").
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The goal of Swedish warfare during the 17th century was to make the Baltic Sea an all-Swedish sea (*Ett Svenskt innanhav*), something that was accomplished except the part between Riga in Latvia and Stettin in Pomerania.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] However, the Dutch dominated the Baltic trade in the seventeenth century.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the eighteenth century, Russia and Prussia became the leading powers over the sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Sweden's defeat in the Great Northern War brought Russia to the eastern coast.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Russia became and remained a dominating power in the Baltic.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Russia's Peter the Great saw the strategic importance of the Baltic and decided to found his new capital, Saint Petersburg, at the mouth of the Neva river at the east end of the Gulf of Finland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] There was much trading not just within the Baltic region but also with the North Sea region, especially eastern England and the Netherlands: their fleets needed the Baltic timber, tar, flax, and hemp.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] During the Crimean War, a joint British and French fleet attacked the Russian fortresses in the Baltic; the case is also known as the Åland War.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] They bombarded Sveaborg, which guards Helsinki; and Kronstadt, which guards Saint Petersburg; and they destroyed Bomarsund in Åland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] After the unification of Germany in 1871, the whole southern coast became German.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] World War I was partly fought in the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] After 1920 Poland was granted access to the Baltic Sea at the expense of Germany by the Polish Corridor and enlarged the port of Gdynia in rivalry with the port of the Free City of Danzig.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] After the Nazis' rise to power, Germany reclaimed the Memelland and after the outbreak of the Eastern Front (World War II) occupied the Baltic states.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In 1945, the Baltic Sea became a mass grave for retreating soldiers and refugees on torpedoed troop transports.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The sinking of the *Wilhelm Gustloff* remains the worst maritime disaster in history, killing (very roughly) 9,000 people.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In 2005, a Russian group of scientists found over five thousand airplane wrecks, sunken warships, and other material, mainly from World War II, on the bottom of the sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Since the end of World War II, various nations, including the Soviet Union, the United Kingdom and the United States have disposed of chemical weapons in the Baltic Sea, raising concerns of environmental contamination.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Today, fishermen occasionally find some of these materials: the most recent available report from the Helsinki Commission notes that four small scale catches of chemical munitions representing approximately 105 kg (231 lb) of material were reported in 2005.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] This is a reduction from the 25 incidents representing 1,110 kg (2,450 lb) of material in 2003.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Government refuses to disclose the exact coordinates of the wreck sites.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Deteriorating bottles leak mustard gas and other substances, thus slowly poisoning a substantial part of the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In addition to chemicals, tons of German ammunition were dumped into the Baltic after the war at the behest of the Allies, who wanted to ensure that they would not start another war.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] By 2025, these were leaking contaminants into the water and the German government was piloting solutions.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] After 1945, the German population was expelled from all areas east of the Oder-Neisse line, making room for new Polish and Russian settlement.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Poland gained most of the southern shore.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Soviet Union gained another access to the Baltic with the Kaliningrad Oblast, that had been part of German-settled East Prussia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic states on the eastern shore were annexed by the Soviet Union.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic then separated opposing military blocs: NATO and the Warsaw Pact.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] During the Cold War the Baltic Sea remained on the periphery of the main axis of confrontation between these two blocs.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Neutral Sweden developed incident weapons to defend its territorial waters after the Swedish submarine incidents.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] This border status restricted trade and travel.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It ended only after the collapse of the Communist regimes in Central and Eastern Europe in the late 1980s.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Finland and Sweden joined NATO in 2023 and 2024, respectively, making the Baltic Sea almost entirely surrounded by the alliance's members, leading some commentators to label the sea a "NATO lake".
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] However, the legal status of the sea has not changed and it is still open to all nations.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Such an arrangement has also existed for the European Union (EU) since May 2004 following the accession of the Baltic states and Poland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The remaining non-NATO and non-EU shore areas are Russian: the Saint Petersburg area and the Kaliningrad Oblast exclave.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea today is of significant economic and security importance due to its dense network of submarine cables, energy pipelines, ports and offshore energy platforms.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In recent years, there have been a number of incidents of sabotage in the Baltic Sea, resulting in damage to critical infrastructures.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The most notable incidents include the Nord Stream pipelines sabotage in 2022, where a series of underwater explosions destroyed both Nord Stream 1 and 2.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In 2023, there was another incident involving the Balticconnector gas pipeline and a nearby data cable, which were damaged by the Hong Kong-flagged container ship NewNew Polar Bear.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Other significant incidents include the recent damage to several undersea communication cables.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The most recent incident of relevance was the rupture of the Estlink 2 cable in late 2024.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It is suspected that the oil tanker Eagle S, believed to be part of a Russian shadow fleet, is responsible.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] These events followed a series of responses from both NATO and the EU.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In response, NATO Baltic Sea states have increased their naval presence in the Baltic Sea, and the NATO operation Baltic Sentry was established.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Simultaneously, the EU has implemented a series of measures designed to enhance the protection of critical maritime infrastructure.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The EU has also underscored the commitment to strengthening cooperation with NATO.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Winter storms begin arriving in the region during October.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] These have caused numerous shipwrecks, and contributed to the extreme difficulties of rescuing passengers of the ferry MS *Estonia* en route from Tallinn, Estonia, to Stockholm, Sweden, in September 1994, which claimed the lives of 852 people.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Older, wood-based shipwrecks such as the *Vasa* tend to remain well-preserved, as the Baltic's cold and brackish water does not suit the shipworm.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Storm surge floods are generally taken to occur when the water level is more than one metre above normal.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In Warnemünde about 110 floods occurred from 1950 to 2000, an average of just over two per year.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Historic flood events were the All Saints' Flood of 1304 and other floods in the years 1320, 1449, 1625, 1694, 1784 and 1825.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] From 1872, there exist regular and reliable records of water levels in the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The highest was the flood of 1872 when the water was an average of 2.43 m (8 ft 0 in) above sea level at Warnemünde and a maximum of 2.83 m (9 ft 3 in) above sea level in Warnemünde.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the last very heavy floods the average water levels reached 1.88 m (6 ft 2 in) above sea level in 1904, 1.89 m (6 ft 2 in) in 1913, 1.73 m (5 ft 8 in) in January 1954, 1.68 m (5 ft 6 in) on 2–4 November 1995 and 1.65 m (5 ft 5 in) on 21 February 2002.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] An arm of the North Atlantic Ocean, the Baltic Sea is enclosed by Sweden and Denmark to the west, Finland to the northeast, and the Baltic countries to the southeast.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It is about 1,600 km (990 mi) long, an average of 193 km (120 mi) wide, and an average of 55 metres (180 ft) deep.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The maximum depth is 459 m (1,506 ft) which is on the Swedish side of the centre.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The periphery amounts to about 8,000 km (5,000 mi) of coastline.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea is one of the largest brackish inland seas by area, and occupies a basin (a *Zungenbecken*) formed by glacial erosion during the last few ice ages.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The northern part of the Baltic Sea is known as the Gulf of Bothnia, of which the northernmost part is the Bay of Bothnia or Bothnian Bay.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The more rounded southern basin of the gulf is called Bothnian Sea and immediately to the south of it lies the Sea of Åland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Gulf of Finland connects the Baltic Sea with Saint Petersburg.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Gulf of Riga lies between the Latvian capital city of Riga and the Estonian island of Saaremaa.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Northern Baltic Sea lies between the Stockholm area, southwestern Finland, and Estonia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Western and Eastern Gotland basins form the major parts of the Central Baltic Sea or Baltic proper.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Bornholm Basin is the area east of Bornholm, and the shallower Arkona Basin extends from Bornholm to the Danish isles of Falster and Zealand.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the south, the Bay of Gdańsk lies east of the Hel Peninsula on the Polish coast and west of the Sambia Peninsula in Kaliningrad Oblast.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Bay of Pomerania lies north of the islands of Usedom/Uznam and Wolin, east of Rügen.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Between Falster and the German coast lie the Bay of Mecklenburg and Bay of Lübeck.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The westernmost part of the Baltic Sea is the Bay of Kiel.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The three Danish Straits, the Great Belt, the Little Belt and The Sound (*Öresund*/*Øresund*), connect the Baltic Sea with the Kattegat and Skagerrak strait in the North Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The water temperature of the Baltic Sea varies significantly depending on exact location, season and depth.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] At the Bornholm Basin, which is located directly east of the island of the same name, the surface temperature typically falls to 0–5 °C (32–41 °F) during the peak of the winter and rises to 15–20 °C (59–68 °F) during the peak of the summer, with an annual average of around 9–10 °C (48–50 °F).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] A similar pattern can be seen in the Gotland Basin, which is located between the island of Gotland and Latvia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the deep of these basins the temperature variations are smaller.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] At the bottom of the Bornholm Basin, deeper than 80 m (260 ft), the temperature typically is 1–10 °C (34–50 °F), and at the bottom of the Gotland Basin, at depths greater than 225 m (738 ft), the temperature typically is 4–7 °C (39–45 °F).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Generally, offshore locations, lower latitudes and islands maintain maritime climates, but adjacent to the water continental climates are common, especially on the Gulf of Finland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the northern tributaries the climates transition from moderate continental to subarctic on the northernmost coastlines.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] On the long-term average, the Baltic Sea is ice-covered at the annual maximum for about 45% of its surface area.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The ice-covered area during such a typical winter includes the Gulf of Bothnia, the Gulf of Finland, the Gulf of Riga, the archipelago west of Estonia, the Stockholm archipelago, and the Archipelago Sea southwest of Finland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The remainder of the Baltic does not freeze during a normal winter, except sheltered bays and shallow lagoons such as the Curonian Lagoon.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The ice reaches its maximum extent in February or March; typical ice thickness in the northernmost areas in the Bothnian Bay, the northern basin of the Gulf of Bothnia, is about 70 cm (28 in) for landfast sea ice.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Freezing begins in the northern extremities of the Gulf of Bothnia typically in the middle of November, reaching the open waters of the Bothnian Bay in early January.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Bothnian Sea, the basin south of Kvarken, freezes on average in late February.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Gulf of Finland and the Gulf of Riga freeze typically in late January.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In 2011, the Gulf of Finland was completely frozen on 15 February.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The ice extent depends on whether the winter is mild, moderate, or severe.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In severe winters ice can form around southern Sweden and even in the Danish Straits.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] According to the 18th-century natural historian William Derham, during the severe winters of 1703 and 1708, the ice cover reached as far as the Danish Straits.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Frequently, parts of the Gulf of Bothnia and the Gulf of Finland are frozen, in addition to coastal fringes in more southerly locations such as the Gulf of Riga.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] This description meant that the whole of the Baltic Sea was covered with ice.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Since 1720, the Baltic Sea has frozen over entirely 20 times, most recently in early 1987, which was the most severe winter in Scandinavia since 1720.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] During the winter of 2010–11, which was quite severe compared to those of the last decades, the maximum ice cover was 315,000 km2 (122,000 sq mi), which was reached on 25 February 2011.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The ice then extended from the north down to the northern tip of Gotland, with small ice-free areas on either side, and the east coast of the Baltic Sea was covered by an ice sheet about 25 to 100 km (16 to 62 mi) wide all the way to Gdańsk.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] This was brought about by a stagnant high-pressure area that lingered over central and northern Scandinavia from around 10 to 24 February.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] After this, strong southern winds pushed the ice further into the north, and much of the waters north of Gotland were again free of ice, which had then packed against the shores of southern Finland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The effects of the aforementioned high-pressure area did not reach the southern parts of the Baltic Sea, and thus the entire sea did not freeze over.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] However, floating ice was additionally observed near Świnoujście harbour in January 2010.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In recent years before 2011, the Bothnian Bay and the Bothnian Sea were frozen with solid ice near the Baltic coast and dense floating ice far from it.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In 2008, almost no ice formed except for a short period in March.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] During winter, fast ice, which is attached to the shoreline, develops first, rendering ports unusable without the services of icebreakers.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Level ice, ice sludge, pancake ice, and rafter ice form in the more open regions.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The gleaming expanse of ice is similar to the Arctic, with wind-driven pack ice and ridges up to 15 m (49 ft).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Offshore of the landfast ice, the ice remains very dynamic all year, and it is relatively easily moved around by winds and therefore forms pack ice, made up of large piles and ridges pushed against the landfast ice and shores.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In spring, the Gulf of Finland and the Gulf of Bothnia normally thaw in late April, with some ice ridges persisting until May in the eastern extremities of the Gulf of Finland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the northernmost reaches of the Bothnian Bay, ice usually stays until late May; by early June it is practically always gone.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] However, in the famine year of 1867 remnants of ice were observed as late as 17 July near Uddskär.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Even as far south as Øresund, remnants of ice have been observed in May on several occasions; near Taarbaek on 15 May 1942 and near Copenhagen on 11 May 1771.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Drift ice was also observed on 11 May 1799.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The ice cover is the main habitat for two large mammals, the grey seal (*Halichoerus grypus*) and the Baltic ringed seal (*Pusa hispida botnica*), both of which feed underneath the ice and breed on its surface.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Of these two seals, only the Baltic ringed seal suffers when there is not adequate ice in the Baltic Sea, as it feeds its young only while on ice.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The grey seal is adapted to reproducing also with no ice in the sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The sea ice also harbours several species of algae that live in the bottom and inside unfrozen brine pockets in the ice.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Due to the often fluctuating winter temperatures between above and below freezing, the saltwater ice of the Baltic Sea can be treacherous and hazardous to walk on, in particular in comparison to the more stable fresh water-ice sheets in the interior lakes.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea flows out through the Danish Straits; however, the flow is complex.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] A surface layer of brackish water discharges 940 km3 (230 cu mi) per year into the North Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Due to the difference in salinity, by salinity permeation principle, a sub-surface layer of more saline water moving in the opposite direction brings in 475 km3 (114 cu mi) per year.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It mixes very slowly with the upper waters, resulting in a salinity gradient from top to bottom, with most of the saltwater remaining below 40 to 70 m (130 to 230 ft) deep.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The general circulation is anti-clockwise: northwards along its eastern boundary, and south along with the western one.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The difference between the outflow and the inflow comes entirely from fresh water.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] More than 250 streams drain a basin of about 1,600,000 km2 (620,000 sq mi), contributing a volume of 660 km3 (160 cu mi) per year to the Baltic.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] They include the major rivers of north Europe, such as the Oder, the Vistula, the Neman, the Daugava and the Neva.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Additional fresh water comes from the difference of precipitation less evaporation, which is positive.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] An important source of salty water is infrequent inflows (also known as major Baltic inflows or MBIs) of North Sea water into the Baltic.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Such inflows, important to the Baltic ecosystem because of the oxygen they transport into the Baltic deeps, happen on average once per year, but large pulses that can replace the anoxic deep water in the Gotland Deep occur about once in ten years.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Previously, it was believed that the frequency of MBIs had declined since 1980, but recent studies have challenged this view and no longer display a clear change in the frequency or intensity of saline inflows.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Instead, a decadal variability in the intensities of MBIs is observed with a main period of approximately 30 years.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The water level is generally far more dependent on the regional wind situation than on tidal effects.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] However, tidal currents occur in narrow passages in the western parts of the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Tides can reach 17 to 19 cm (6.7 to 7.5 in) in the Gulf of Finland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The significant wave height is generally much lower than that of the North Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Quite violent, sudden storms sweep the surface ten or more times a year, due to large transient temperature differences and a long reach of the wind.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Seasonal winds also cause small changes in sea level, of the order of 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) .
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] According to the media, during a storm in January 2017, an extreme wave above 14 m (46 ft) has been measured and significant wave height of around 8 m (26 ft) has been measured by the FMI.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] A numerical study has shown the presence of events with 8 to 10 m (26 to 33 ft) significant wave heights.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Those extreme waves events can play an important role in the coastal zone on erosion and sea dynamics.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea is the world's largest brackish sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Only two other brackish waters are larger according to some measurements: The Black Sea is larger in both surface area and water volume, but most of it is located outside the continental shelf (only a small fraction is inland).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Caspian Sea is larger in water volume, but—despite its name—it is a lake rather than a sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The open surface waters of the Baltic Sea "proper" generally have a salinity of 0.3 to 0.9%, which is border-line freshwater.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The flow of freshwater into the sea from approximately two hundred rivers and the introduction of salt from the southwest builds up a gradient of salinity in the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The highest surface salinities, generally 0.7–0.9%, are in the southwestern most part of the Baltic, in the Arkona and Bornholm basins (the former located roughly between southeast Zealand and Bornholm, and the latter directly east of Bornholm).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] It gradually falls further east and north, reaching the lowest in the Bothnian Bay at around 0.3%.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Drinking the surface water of the Baltic as a means of survival would actually hydrate the body instead of dehydrating, as is the case with ocean water.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] As saltwater is denser than freshwater, the bottom of the Baltic Sea is saltier than the surface.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] This creates a vertical stratification of the water column, a halocline, that represents a barrier to the exchange of oxygen and nutrients, and fosters completely separate maritime environments.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The difference between the bottom and surface salinities varies depending on location.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Overall it follows the same southwest to east and north pattern as the surface.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] At the bottom of the Arkona Basin (equalling depths greater than 40 m or 130 ft) and Bornholm Basin (depths greater than 80 m or 260 ft) it is typically 1.4–1.8%.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Further east and north the salinity at the bottom is consistently lower, being the lowest in Bothnian Bay (depths greater than 120 m or 390 ft) where it is slightly below 0.4%, or only marginally higher than the surface in the same region.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In contrast, the salinity of the Danish Straits, which connect the Baltic Sea and Kattegat, tends to be significantly higher, but with major variations from year to year.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] For example, the surface and bottom salinity in the Great Belt is typically around 2.0% and 2.8% respectively, which is only somewhat below that of the Kattegat.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The water surplus caused by the continuous inflow of rivers and streams to the Baltic Sea means that there generally is a flow of brackish water out through the Danish Straits to the Kattegat (and eventually the Atlantic).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Significant flows in the opposite direction, salt water from the Kattegat through the Danish Straits to the Baltic Sea, are less regular and are known as major Baltic inflows (MBIs).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The rating of mean discharges differs from the ranking of hydrological lengths (from the most distant source to the sea) and the rating of the nominal lengths.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Countries that border the sea: Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Germany, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Russia, Sweden.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Countries lands in the outer drainage basin: Belarus, Czech Republic, Norway, Slovakia, Ukraine.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea drainage basin is roughly four times the surface area of the sea itself.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] About 48% of the region is forested, with Sweden and Finland containing the majority of the forest, especially around the Gulfs of Bothnia and Finland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] About 20% of the land is used for agriculture and pasture, mainly in Poland and around the edge of the Baltic Proper, in Germany, Denmark, and Sweden.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] About 17% of the basin is unused open land with another 8% of wetlands.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Most of the latter are in the Gulfs of Bothnia and Finland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The rest of the land is heavily populated.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] About 85 million people live in the Baltic drainage basin, 15 million within 10 km (6 mi) of the coast and 29 million within 50 km (31 mi) of the coast.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Around 22 million live in population centres of over 250,000.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] 90% of these are concentrated in the 10 km (6 mi) band around the coast.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Of the nations containing all or part of the basin, Poland includes 45% of the 85 million, Russia 12%, Sweden 10% and the others less than 6% each.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The relic of Scandinavian Glacier in white.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] is former seabed or archipelago: illustrated are sea levels immediately after the last ice age.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The Baltic Sea somewhat resembles a riverbed, with two tributaries, the Gulf of Finland and Gulf of Bothnia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Geological surveys show that before the Pleistocene, instead of the Baltic Sea, there was a wide plain around a great river that palaeontologists call the Eridanos.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Several Pleistocene glacial episodes scooped out the river bed into the sea basin.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] By the time of the last, or Eemian Stage (MIS 5e), the Eemian Sea was in place.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Sometimes the Baltic Sea is considered a very large estuary, with freshwater outflow from numerous rivers.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] From that time the waters underwent a geologic history summarized under the names listed below.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Many of the stages are named after marine animals (e.g. the Littorina mollusc) that are clear markers of changing water temperatures and salinity.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The land is still emerging isostatically from its depressed state, which was caused by the weight of ice during the last glaciation.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The phenomenon is known as post-glacial rebound.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] Consequently, the surface area and the depth of the sea are diminishing.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] The uplift is about eight millimetres per year on the Finnish coast of the northernmost Gulf of Bothnia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p01] In the area, the former seabed is only gently sloping, leading to large areas of land being reclaimed in what are, geologically speaking, relatively short periods (decades and centuries).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The fauna of the Baltic Sea is a mixture of marine and freshwater species.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Among marine fishes are Atlantic cod, Atlantic herring, European hake, European plaice, European flounder, shorthorn sculpin and turbot, and examples of freshwater species include European perch, northern pike, whitefish and common roach.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Freshwater species may occur at outflows of rivers or streams in all coastal sections of the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Otherwise, marine species dominate in most sections of the Baltic, at least as far north as Gävle, where less than one-tenth are freshwater species.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In the Bothnian Bay, roughly two-thirds of the species are freshwater.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In the far north of this bay, saltwater species are almost entirely absent.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] For example, the common starfish and shore crab, two species that are very widespread along European coasts, are both unable to cope with the significantly lower salinity.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Their range limit is west of Bornholm, meaning that they are absent from the vast majority of the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Some marine species, like the Atlantic cod and European flounder, can survive at relatively low salinities but need higher salinities to breed, which therefore occurs in deeper parts of the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The common blue mussel is the dominating animal species, and makes up more than 90% of the total animal biomass in the sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] There is a decrease in species richness from the Danish belts to the Gulf of Bothnia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The decreasing salinity along this path causes restrictions in both physiology and habitats.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] However, even the most diverse sections of the Baltic Sea have far fewer species than the almost-full saltwater Kattegat, which is home to more than 1600 species from these groups.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The lack of tides has affected the marine species as compared with the Atlantic.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Since the Baltic Sea is so young there are only two or three known endemic species: the brown alga *Fucus radicans* and the flounder *Platichthys solemdali*.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Both appear to have evolved in the Baltic basin and were only recognized as species in 2005 and 2018 respectively, having formerly been confused with more widespread relatives.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The tiny Copenhagen cockle (*Parvicardium hauniense*), a rare mussel, is sometimes considered endemic, but has now been recorded in the Mediterranean.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] However, some consider non-Baltic records to be misidentifications of juvenile lagoon cockles (*Cerastoderma glaucum*).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Several widespread marine species have distinctive subpopulations in the Baltic Sea adapted to the low salinity, such as the Baltic Sea forms of the Atlantic herring and lumpsucker, which are smaller than the widespread forms in the North Atlantic.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] A peculiar feature of the fauna is that it contains a number of glacial relict species, isolated populations of arctic species which have remained in the Baltic Sea since the last glaciation, such as the large isopod *Saduria entomon*, the Baltic subspecies of ringed seal, and the fourhorn sculpin.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Some of these relicts are derived from glacial lakes, such as *Monoporeia affinis*, which is a main element in the benthic fauna of the low-salinity Bothnian Bay.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Cetaceans in the Baltic Sea are monitored by the countries bordering the sea and data compiled by various intergovernmental bodies, such as ASCOBANS.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In recent years, very small, but with increasing rates, fin whales and humpback whales migrate into Baltic sea including mother and calf pair.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Now extinct Atlantic grey whales (remains found from Gräsö along Bothnian Sea/southern Bothnian Gulf and Ystad) and eastern population of North Atlantic right whales that is facing functional extinction once migrated into Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Other notable megafauna include the basking sharks.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Satellite images taken in July 2010 revealed a massive algal bloom covering 377,000 square kilometres (146,000 mi2) in the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The area of the bloom extended from Germany and Poland to Finland.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Researchers of the phenomenon have found that algal blooms have occurred every summer for decades.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Fertilizer runoff from surrounding agricultural land has exacerbated the problem and led to increased eutrophication.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Approximately 100,000 km2 (38,610 sq mi) of the Baltic's seafloor (a quarter of its total area) is a variable dead zone.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The more saline (and therefore denser) water remains on the bottom, isolating it from surface waters and the atmosphere.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] This leads to decreased oxygen concentrations within the zone.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] It is mainly bacteria that grow in it, digesting organic material and releasing hydrogen sulfide.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Because of this large anaerobic zone, the seafloor ecology differs from that of the neighbouring Atlantic.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Plans to artificially oxygenate areas of the Baltic that have experienced eutrophication have been proposed by the University of Gothenburg and Inocean AB.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The proposal intends to use wind-driven pumps to pump oxygen-rich surface water to a depth of around 130 m.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] After World War II, Germany had to be disarmed, and large quantities of ammunition stockpiles were disposed directly into the Baltic Sea and the North Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Environmental experts and marine biologists warn that these ammunition dumps pose an environmental threat, with potentially life-threatening consequences to the health and safety of humans on the coastlines of these seas.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Climate change, and pollution from agriculture and forestry, impose such strong effects on the ecosystems of the Baltic sea, that there is a concern the sea will turn from a carbon sink to a source of carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] These include its current brackish water, the southern subbasin tendency to have a vertical stratification of the halocline, and the northern subbasin seasonal sea ice cover.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] There are many more projections but these have lower confidence.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Construction of the Great Belt Bridge in Denmark (completed 1997) and the Øresund Bridge-Tunnel (completed 1999), linking Denmark with Sweden, provided a highway and railroad connection between Sweden and the Danish mainland (the Jutland Peninsula, precisely the Zealand).
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The undersea tunnel of the Øresund Bridge-Tunnel provides for navigation of large ships into and out of the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The Baltic Sea is the main trade route for the export of Russian petroleum.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Countries neighbouring the Baltic Sea have expressed concerns about this since a major oil leak in a seagoing tanker would be especially disastrous for the Baltic given the slow exchange of water in the ecosystem.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The tourism industry surrounding the Baltic Sea is naturally concerned about oil pollution.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Much shipbuilding is carried out in the shipyards around the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The largest shipyards are at Gdańsk, Gdynia, and Szczecin, Poland; Kiel, Germany; Karlskrona and Malmö, Sweden; Rauma, Turku, and Helsinki, Finland; Riga, Ventspils, and Liepāja, Latvia; Klaipėda, Lithuania; and Saint Petersburg, Russia.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Construction of the Fehmarn Belt Fixed Link between Denmark and Germany is due to finish in 2029.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] It will be a three-bore tunnel carrying four motorway lanes and two rail tracks.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Through the development of offshore wind power the Baltic Sea is expected to become a major source of energy for countries in the region.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] According to the Marienborg Declaration, signed in 2022, all EU Baltic Sea states have announced their intentions to have 19.6 gigawatts of offshore wind in operation by 2030.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Critical maritime infrastructure (CMI) include pipelines, ports, undersea cables and energy installations.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Following a series of incidents between 2022 and 2025, critical infrastructure in the Baltic Sea has drawn growing political attention.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In September 2022, both Nord Stream I and Nord Stream II were damaged by explosives close to Bornholm in Denmark.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In October 2023, the Balticconnector gas pipeline was damaged by the anchor of the Chinese container vessel *Newnew Polar Bear*.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In November 2024, telecoms cables were damaged, another case of suspected sabotage from a Chinese bulk carrier, departing from a Russian port.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In December 2024, a ship registered in the Cook Islands which was thought to be part of a Russian shadow fleet, the *Estlink 2*, was suspected to have damaged internet cables.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] These incidents have led to responses from NATO, the European Union and national governments.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] NATO has increased its air and naval presence, as well as agreed to establish the Maritime Centre for the Security of Critical Undersea Infrastructure within NATO's Allied Maritime Command (MARCOM), among other cooperation efforts.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The EU has updated its Maritime Security Strategy, launched an action plan and a coordination group for infrastructure protection, while national governments have strengthened surveillance, legal tools, and seabed defence capabilities.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Aside from technical standards, political decisions influence what is deemed as "critical" infrastructure.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Critical maritime infrastructure is deemed as critical since economies in today's society are dependent on this infrastructure.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Therefore, they require an extra layer of protection, whether by security policies or military protection.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In the current geopolitical climate, CMI is facing challenges posed by hybrid warfare threats.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Hybrid threats in the Baltic Sea are often associated with Russian actions and operate below the official threshold of war, which poses a political challenge.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The challenge posed by hybrid threats is that they operate in a grey area between peace and violence.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] For example, the Nord Stream pipeline sabotage demonstrated this problem by exploitation of legal ambiguities, the complexity of attribution, and the disruption of alliance cohesion.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The incident highlights the vulnerability of critical infrastructure and the absence of coherent political responses.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Responding to hybrid threats requires sustained and coordinated efforts between civilian and military actors.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] However, the maritime domain presents unique difficulties, including jurisdictional overlaps, fragmented responsibilities, and the challenge of adapting land-based security frameworks to the sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Hybrid tactics, such as uncrewed aerial vehicle (drone) surveillance, covert sabotage, and information manipulation, aim not only to damage infrastructure but also to undermine public trust and create strategic instability in the region.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The Baltic Sea region in the post-Cold War era has for a long time been regarded as an area with little geopolitical tensions.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] With the Soviet presence in the south, the American influence through the NATO members Denmark and Germany and the neutral states Sweden and Finland, an equilibrium existed, often referred to as the "Nordic balance".
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] This balance also prolonged after the steady integration of the region into western institutions.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] However, in recent years this geopolitical reality has increasingly been challenged by the neo-imperial ambitions of Russia, manifesting itself in aggression against Ukraine.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Russia has also pursued a strategy of regional dominance in the Baltic Sea, designating the regional sea as a zone of strategic influence in its naval doctrine published in 2022.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Yet, such a positioning in itself was significantly complicated by the accession of Sweden and Finland to NATO.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Against this geopolitical background, it becomes clear, why many of the recent infrastructure projects in the Baltic Sea were subject to big political debates.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] These initiatives form part of broader efforts to enhance regional integration and bring the Baltic Sea states into closer alignment with the European Union.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In contrast, the Nord Stream pipelines, particularly Nord Stream 2, became a source of political controversy.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Critics argued that the project would increase European dependence on Russian gas, bypass transit countries such as Ukraine and Poland, and undermine EU energy solidarity by strengthening Russia's leverage over countries like Germany.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Nord Stream 2 experienced prolonged delays and was ultimately suspended following the imposition of international sanctions against Russia after the invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In addition to political and economic controversies, the Nord Stream pipelines also became the subject of security-related concerns regarding their potential strategic implications in the Baltic Sea region.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Prior to the 2022 sabotage of the Nord Stream pipelines, security experts and several Eastern European states had raised concerns that such infrastructure could be exploited by Russia for intelligence gathering and military purposes in the Baltic Sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] These concerns gained renewed attention following the sabotage incident, which highlighted challenges in the legal and regulatory frameworks governing the protection of critical infrastructure.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The difficulty in conclusively attributing the attack also drew attention to the limitations of existing mechanisms for responding to hybrid threats in the maritime domain.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] For the first time ever, all the sources of pollution around an entire sea were made subject to a single convention, signed in 1974 by the then seven Baltic coastal states.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The 1974 Convention entered into force on 3 May 1980.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] In the light of political changes and developments in international environmental and maritime law, a new convention was signed in 1992 by all the states bordering on the Baltic Sea, and the European Community.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] After ratification, the Convention entered into force on 17 January 2000.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The Convention covers the whole of the Baltic Sea area, including inland waters and the water of the sea itself, as well as the seabed.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Measures are also taken in the whole catchment area of the Baltic Sea to reduce land-based pollution.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The convention on the Protection of the Marine Environment of the Baltic Sea Area, 1992, entered into force on 17 January 2000.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The governing body of the convention is the Helsinki Commission, also known as HELCOM, or Baltic Marine Environment Protection Commission.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The present contracting parties are Denmark, Estonia, the European Community, Finland, Germany, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Russia, and Sweden.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The ratification instruments were deposited by the European Community, Germany, Latvia and Sweden in 1994, by Estonia and Finland in 1995, by Denmark in 1996, by Lithuania in 1997, and by Poland and Russia in November 1999.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The European Union (EU) is one core framework shaping regional security coordination in the Baltic Sea region.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The EU has recognised this area as one of thirteen designated zones for territorial cooperation.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Following the accession of the Baltic States in 2004, the Baltic Sea is now considered an EU internal sea.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The North Atlantic Treaty Organisation (NATO) is the primary provider of a collective defence system.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] Following the accession of Finland in 2023 and Sweden in 2024, the majority of the states bordering the Baltic Sea have become members of NATO, simplifying the organisational geography of the region.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The Nordic Defence Cooperation (NORDEFCO) is a military alliance comprising the Nordic countries of Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway and Sweden.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The objectives of this cooperation structure include improving the national defence of each country, identifying shared strategic interests, and promoting the development of coordinated, effective responses.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The strategy paper 'Vision 2025' outlines plans to enhance collaboration with the Baltic states and transatlantic allies.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The Council of the Baltic Sea States is an intergovernmental political organisation that focuses on regional cooperation.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] It was established in 1992 and comprises ten European states and the European Union.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] The organisation serves as a forum for political dialogue in the region and follows three main objectives: Regional Identity, Safe & Secure Region, and Sustainable & Prosperous Region.
[src:floating-battery/baltic-sea-p02] It holds annual regional and international meetings.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] The **Banjarese** (Banjar: *Urang Banjar*, Jawi script: اورڠ بنجر; Indonesian: *Orang Banjar*) or simply **Banjar**, are an Austronesian ethnic group native to the Banjar regions (notably Banjarmasin, Banjarbaru, Banjar Regency, etc.) in the southeastern Kalimantan regions of Indonesia.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] Nowadays, Banjarese diaspora can be found in neighbouring Banjar regions as well; including Kotabaru Regency, the southeastern regions of Central Kalimantan, southernmost regions of East Kalimantan, and some provinces of Indonesia in general.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] The Banjarese diaspora community also can be found in neighbouring countries of Indonesia, such as Brunei, Malaysia (notably in Perak, Selangor, Kedah, and Johor, with significant minorities in Sabah), and Singapore.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] The Banjars form the major indigenous group within the southern coast of the South Kalimantan region, which is rich in history, traditional heritage, and various attire and language as well as customs.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] The Batang Banyu dialect, meanwhile, is a distinct variant of the Banjarese language, featuring unique vocabulary and pronunciations that differ from the two major dialects of Kuala Banjar and Hulu Banjar.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] The word *Banjar* is believed to have originated from the word *Banjarmasih*, which was once a village for Malay ethnic groups located at the mouth of the Kuwin River, a tributary of the Barito River.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] *Banjar* carries the meaning of "village" while *Masih* is the name of a Malay tribal chief or *Patih*—the Ngaju Dayak people refer to this Malay tribal chief of "*Patih Masih*" as "*Oloh Masih*".
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] Another version states that the word means "rows", which turns into a row of houses, villages, hamlets, or water villages along the South Kalimantan riverbank.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] The word *Banjarmasih* gradually changed to its current pronunciation of *Bandjermasin* (*Banjarmasin*) due to the Dutch pronunciation.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] Based on the Malay-English dictionary written by British colonial administrator and historian Richard James Wilkinson in 1908, *banjar* carries the meaning of *row*, which is also an Old Javanese language.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] The word is also derived from terminology in the Janyawai dialect of the Ma'anyan language, which is also rooted in Old Javanese.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] It is initially used to identified the Ma'anyan, Meratus Dayak, and Ngaju people who are already "Javanised" when the Javanese people arrived in the southeastern Kalimantan regions to establish their civilisation, as recorded in Ma'anyan poetry of "*Nansarunai Usak Jawa*".
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] The term *banjar* (ꦧꦚ꧀ꦗꦂ) itself in Javanese language is a short form of a verb *mbanjarke* (ꦩ꧀ꦧꦚ꧀ꦗꦂꦏꦺ), which means "to separate and rearrange" literally.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] It is 'common knowledge' within the communities of South Kalimantan that the Banjarese people were formerly part of larger Dayak community.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] Around 2500 BC, the Austronesian people began to migrate into Borneo from an area in South China through Taiwan and the Philippines archipelago.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] Later, in 400 AD, the Indianised cultural influences, rather than a direct mass migration solely from Sumatra, were spread to Borneo, as evidenced by the Yūpa inscriptions found in Kutai, East Kalimantan.
[src:floating-battery/banjar-people] In 520 AD, Sumatran immigrants further formed the Buddhist Kingdom of Tanjungpuri in the present-day region of Tanjung, Tabalong.
